const CITY_WINDOW_SUPPLEMENTAL = {
  "los-angeles-ca": {
    sec_energy2: `LA's Title 24 cool-glazing provisions were stiffened in the 2022 code cycle and again in 2025-effective amendments: SHGC on west-facing glazing capped at 0.23 in new construction and 0.40 in alterations, with compliance verified at permit final. Meeting that number requires spectrally-selective Low-E coatings tuned for solar rejection; generic Low-E 272 does not qualify. LADWP rebate eligibility is tied to NFRC-certified product only, and unrated replacement windows (common in cash-job retrofits) disqualify the homeowner from rebate recovery regardless of how efficient the product actually is.`,
    sec_installer: `LA installer vetting: verify active CSLB license at cslb.ca.gov (C-17 glazing or B general), confirm workers' compensation coverage specifically (not just general liability, because CSLB publishes these separately), and cross-reference the license-holder name against the company name on the bid. LA has a chronic problem with "broker" operators who hold a license but subcontract the actual work to unlicensed crews, which voids California Homeowners Recovery Fund eligibility if the job fails. Ask to meet the specific crew lead before signing, and confirm their employer matches the licensed entity on your contract.`,
    sec_glass: `LA glass packages weight toward spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west exposures, standard Low-E 272 or dual Low-E 180 on north and east. Argon fill is baseline. Coastal LA properties within three miles of the beach also benefit from laminated outer panes for salt-spray and debris resistance; Malibu and Pacific Palisades properties routinely spec laminated outer panes plus ember-resistant tempered inner panes for WUI Chapter 7A compliance, adding $200-$450 per window above standard dual-pane.`,
  },
  "chicago-il": {
    sec_energy2: `Chicago heating-bill economics reward triple-pane aggressively: winter degree-days from late November through early April drive sustained demand, and 0.22 U-factor replacement windows reduce total annual heating consumption by 15-22% over 1970s-era double-pane. Peoples Gas residential rates in 2026 make that payback math work inside 6-9 years on a typical 12-window bungalow replacement. Chicago also enforces the ComEd Public Benefits Fund audit-verification requirement on any whole-home energy-credit job, which means the installing contractor must coordinate with the blower-door test scheduler before final payment releases.`,
    sec_installer: `Chicago installer vetting requires two independent license checks: Illinois has no statewide residential contractor license, but Chicago DOB mandates a General Contractor license for permit-pulling, and the Chicago Department of Finance separately requires a business tax registration. Both must be active on the day of contract signing. Chicago DOB publishes complaint history at chicago.gov/city/en/depts/bldgs, and Illinois Attorney General Home Repair Fraud complaints are searchable at illinoisattorneygeneral.gov.`,
    sec_glass: `Chicago glass packages weight heavily toward triple-pane with Low-E 272 coatings to retain winter solar gain while reducing heat loss. Krypton fill (vs argon) adds another 0.03-0.05 to U-factor reduction at modest cost premium ($75-$125 per window). Chicago also sees meaningful demand for laminated outer panes on lower-floor windows as security upgrade; Chicago BBB complaint data flags home-break-in recovery as a common laminated-glass use case rather than weather-driven.`,
  },
  "houston-tx": {
    sec_energy2: `Houston cooling-bill economics center on SHGC and afternoon-peak load management. CenterPoint's variable pricing rate plans penalize 4-7 PM peak usage, and west-facing glazing drives that peak. Upgrading west-elevation windows alone to SHGC 0.23 spectrally-selective Low-E can shave 15-25% off a Houston home's summer peak-hour demand charges on a variable-rate plan. Houston's sales tax exemption on qualifying ENERGY STAR products (during annual Q3 sales tax holiday) also applies to impact-rated windows purchased during the holiday window.`,
    sec_installer: `Houston installer vetting centers on verifying local bond and insurance (Texas has no state installer license), checking Harris County Appraisal District records if the contractor claims a permanent business address, and cross-referencing Better Business Bureau (bbb.org/houston) complaint history by exact legal entity name. Post-storm windows demand surges every spring, and out-of-state storm response crews concentrate in Houston from March through June. Always pull three independent bids and never sign on an unsolicited door-to-door pitch.`,
    sec_glass: `Houston glass packages prioritize SHGC reduction over U-factor: spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on all exposures, with Low-E 272 acceptable only on deeply-shaded north-elevation openings. Argon fill is baseline, laminated inner pane is the Winter Storm Uri lesson-learned retrofit for freeze-crack resistance, adding $100-$200 per window. Houston also sees premium credits from Texas insurers for FPA-approved or Miami-Dade NOA windows even outside the TWIA zone, which is worth factoring into whole-home budget decisions.`,
  },
  "phoenix-az": {
    sec_energy2: `Phoenix cooling-bill economics reward aggressive SHGC reduction above all else. West-facing glazing in July sees 5+ hours of direct sun at 110F+ ambient, and each square foot of unshaded west-facing single-pane loses the home roughly 2,800 BTU/hr to solar gain. Upgrading west elevations to SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E cuts that loss by 70-80%. APS and SRP both track residential peak-hour use, and Phoenix homes with west-facing ENERGY STAR qualified replacement windows routinely drop into the bottom quartile of peak demand charges after a whole-home retrofit.`,
    sec_installer: `Phoenix installer vetting: verify active CR-61 or B-General Commercial license at roc.az.gov (Arizona Registrar of Contractors), check that bond is current, and confirm the license classification matches the specific scope. Phoenix also sees frequent HOA-architectural-approval complications, and the highest-functioning installers include HOA submittal as standard scope. Ask for three HOA-approved reference installs in comparable neighborhoods, and verify those installs held up through at least one full summer (June-September surface-temperature cycle).`,
    sec_glass: `Phoenix glass packages weight toward dual-pane spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west, Low-E 272 acceptable on east and north. SHGC 0.22 or lower is the practical target (below ENERGY STAR's 0.25 threshold) because Phoenix afternoon solar load is severe. White or light-gray vinyl frames, or aluminum-clad wood in light colors, reject enough radiant heat to keep frame surface temperatures below 160F in July; dark bronze frames routinely exceed 180F and accelerate seal failure.`,
  },
  "dallas-tx": {
    sec_energy2: `Dallas energy economics balance cooling and heating almost evenly across the year. Triple-pane rarely pencils out here because heating loads are moderate, but dual-pane spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west elevations is nearly always the ROI winner. Oncor's time-of-use rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage (3-7 PM), and west-elevation SHGC reduction is the fastest path to shaving those peak charges. Federal 25C tax credit (30% up to $600 annually through 2032) applies to qualifying ENERGY STAR Southern-zone products.`,
    sec_installer: `Dallas installer vetting: Texas has no state installer license, so Dallas relies on city Residential Building Registration (required for permit-pulling), active general liability and workers' compensation insurance (certificates verifiable with the insurer), and Better Business Bureau complaint history at bbb.org/dallas. Dallas-specific due diligence: verify the contractor has worked in the Dallas metro for at least three years (not a storm-chase arrival after the 2023 tornado outbreak) and cross-check references from jobs completed pre-2023.`,
    sec_glass: `Dallas glass packages typically specify dual-pane with spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west, standard Low-E 272 on north and east. Argon fill is baseline. Class 4 laminated impact-rated outer panes on west-facing glazing deliver 5-10% homeowners insurance premium reduction on most Dallas policies written after 2022 and are worth bid-comparing as a performance/ROI upgrade.`,
  },
  "atlanta-ga": {
    sec_energy2: `Atlanta energy economics favor a balanced U-factor/SHGC specification because both seasons matter. Georgia Power's residential variable-rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage, and west-facing ENERGY STAR qualified replacement windows typically reduce those peak charges by 8-14% after a whole-home retrofit. Georgia Power also offers a Home Energy Improvement Program rebate stackable with federal 25C tax credit. Atlanta's tree canopy variation matters for SHGC ROI: heavily shaded Druid Hills homes get less benefit from aggressive SHGC reduction than open-subdivision homes in North Fulton or Cherokee County.`,
    sec_installer: `Atlanta installer vetting: verify active Georgia Residential Basic Contractor license at sos.ga.gov (required for jobs over $2,500), confirm bond and workers' compensation coverage, and cross-reference Georgia Attorney General Consumer Protection complaints at law.georgia.gov. Atlanta also has a specific AOB (Assignment of Benefits) fraud pattern: never sign an AOB with a contractor on day one, and use the 10-business-day rescission window under O.C.G.A. §33-24-59.25 if you signed one under pressure.`,
    sec_glass: `Atlanta glass packages typically specify dual-pane with Low-E 366 on south and west exposures, Low-E 272 on north and east. Argon fill baseline, krypton fill optional on triple-pane. Atlanta Arts-and-Crafts and Tudor homes in Morningside and Ansley Park often require true-divided-lite wood windows with historically appropriate muntin profiles, and those specifications disqualify most off-the-shelf vinyl and aluminum-clad offerings.`,
  },
  "denver-co": {
    sec_energy2: `Denver heating-bill economics reward aggressive U-factor reduction: sustained sub-freezing temperatures from November through March drive heating demand, and triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.18 measurably reduce Xcel Energy winter gas and electric bills. Denver also has the high-altitude capillary-tube requirement on argon IGUs, which is non-negotiable for window longevity at 5,280 feet elevation. Xcel's Windsource renewable-energy program also offers modest efficiency-improvement rebates stackable with the standard ENERGY STAR rebate.`,
    sec_installer: `Denver installer vetting: verify Denver Class D (residential) Supervisor License at denvergov.org, confirm bond and insurance coverage, and cross-reference Colorado DORA (Department of Regulatory Agencies) complaint history at dora.colorado.gov. Colorado has no statewide installer license, so Denver city verification is the operative step. Post-hail-event out-of-state crews are the highest-risk Denver category; verify local address and phone number with at least 18 months of continuous operation before signing.`,
    sec_glass: `Denver glass packages weight heavily toward triple-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings to retain winter solar gain. Krypton fill is the performance spec, and high-altitude capillary tubes must be documented on the spec sheet or the IGU will bow and fail within 2-5 years. Laminated outer panes on west and south elevations deliver Front Range hail-damage insurance premium reductions of 5-10% on Denver policies written after 2022.`,
  },
  "seattle-wa": {
    sec_energy2: `Seattle energy economics reward U-factor reduction across all four elevations because the heating season runs mild but long (October through April). Seattle City Light's Energy Smart rebate stacks with federal 25C and delivers meaningful credit on whole-home weatherization. Seattle's electric heat-pump adoption also changes the calculus: a heat-pump-heated Seattle home benefits more from U-factor reduction than from SHGC tuning because solar gain is already minimal in the marine cool climate.`,
    sec_installer: `Seattle installer vetting: confirm active Washington L&I contractor registration at secure.lni.wa.gov, verify bond amount matches job scope (L&I requires bonds scaled to contract size), and cross-reference Washington Attorney General Consumer Protection complaints at atg.wa.gov. L&I publishes registration status with date stamp, so screenshot the verification as part of your signing file. Lapsed-registration contractors forfeit Seattle homeowners' surety recovery rights, and this is the most common Seattle-specific fraud pattern.`,
    sec_glass: `Seattle glass packages typically specify dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings to capture what solar gain is available in the marine cool climate. Argon fill is baseline. Seattle waterfront and airport-flight-path properties benefit materially from laminated inner panes for acoustic attenuation; laminated glazing reduces aircraft noise by 30-40% over standard dual-pane at modest cost premium ($100-$200 per window).`,
  },
  "austin-tx": {
    sec_energy2: `Austin cooling-bill economics center on SHGC reduction on west and south elevations. Austin Energy's variable-rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage (4-8 PM), and west-facing glazing drives that peak. Upgrading west elevations alone to SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E typically shaves 12-20% off a typical Austin home's summer peak demand charges on a variable-rate plan. Austin Energy's green-building program also offers LEED certification credits that increase home resale value on qualifying full-home retrofits.`,
    sec_installer: `Austin installer vetting: verify City of Austin Registered Residential Building Contractor status, confirm bond and insurance coverage, and cross-reference Austin Code Compliance complaint history at austintexas.gov/department/building-inspections. Austin has no state installer license (Texas), so city registration is the operative verification. Austin's rapid growth attracts out-of-area contractors from Houston and DFW with "we're here for the week" pitches; require a permanent Austin address and three local references pre-2023.`,
    sec_glass: `Austin glass packages weight toward dual-pane spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west, Low-E 272 on east and north. Argon fill is baseline. Post-Winter Storm Uri, laminated inner panes with 0.030-inch PVB interlayers have become a common Austin retrofit for freeze-crack resistance, adding $100-$200 per window. Austin Hill Country limestone-faced homes often require specialty flashing details at stone-to-frame transitions.`,
  },
  "san-francisco-ca": {
    sec_energy2: `SF energy economics vary dramatically by microclimate: Sunset and Richmond fog-belt homes see minimal cooling load but sustained heating demand, while Mission and Bernal Heights sun-belt homes see modest cooling load. SHGC optimization matters only on the sun-belt side of the city. PG&E's Home Efficiency Rebate Plus plus BayREN Home+ incentives can stack to $2,000-$3,500 on whole-home retrofits. SF also has specific induction-cooking electrification rebates that stack with window replacement funding on combined retrofits.`,
    sec_installer: `SF installer vetting: verify active CSLB license (C-17 glazing or B general) at cslb.ca.gov, confirm SF DBI city contractor registration, and cross-reference SF DBI complaint history at sfdbi.org. SF lead-safe renovation rules (pre-1978 homes) additionally require EPA RRP certification, which is separately verifiable at epa.gov. SF's dust-control ordinance §3428 imposes HEPA-vacuum cleanup verification before final inspection on lead-impacted projects.`,
    sec_glass: `SF glass packages vary by microclimate: fog-belt Sunset and Richmond homes typically specify Low-E 272 passive coatings to capture available solar gain, while sun-belt Mission and Bernal Heights homes benefit from Low-E 366 spectrally-selective coatings on west exposures. Argon fill is baseline. SF Victorian and Edwardian restoration projects commonly require true-divided-lite wood windows with wavy-glass reproduction on visible elevations, running $1,800-$3,500 per opening.`,
  },
  "las-vegas-nv": {
    sec_energy2: `Las Vegas cooling-bill economics reward aggressive SHGC reduction plus UV-stabilized frame material selection. NV Energy's TOU-D residential rate plan penalizes summer afternoon peak usage (1-7 PM), and west-facing glazing drives that peak in a city where ambient temperatures exceed 105F for 60+ summer days. Vegas also has one of the nation's highest solar radiation indices, and unprotected dark vinyl frames develop measurable degradation by year 6-8. White or light-gray vinyl with UV stabilizers is the durable specification.`,
    sec_installer: `Vegas installer vetting: verify active Nevada State Contractors Board C-8 glazing license at nscb.nv.gov, check bond status, and cross-reference NSCB complaint history. Nevada's deposit-cap law (NRS §624.6245) caps residential contractor deposits at 10% of contract or $1,000 (whichever is less), so any Vegas contract demanding 20-50% upfront is unenforceable. HOA architectural review complications are also common in Summerlin, Anthem, and MacDonald Ranch; require written HOA approval before any custom window order ships.`,
    sec_glass: `Vegas glass packages prioritize SHGC reduction and UV resistance: dual-pane spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on all exposures with extra spec attention to west-facing. Argon fill is baseline, and white or light-gray frame colors avoid the 160F+ frame surface temperatures that accelerate seal failure on darker frames. Laminated outer panes provide dust-storm debris resistance and 3-6% insurance premium reduction on most Vegas homeowners policies.`,
  },
  "philadelphia-pa": {
    sec_energy2: `Philadelphia rowhouse energy economics differ from detached single-family housing: shared walls with adjacent units eliminate heat loss on those elevations, so window performance on front and back elevations drives nearly all heating-bill reduction. PECO rebate stacking with PGW conservation credits returns meaningful cash on qualifying whole-home retrofits. Pennsylvania Housing Finance Agency low-interest financing also funds whole-home weatherization at below-market rates for qualifying income-eligible homeowners.`,
    sec_installer: `Philly installer vetting: verify both Philadelphia L&I Contractor License (at philadelphialicense.com) AND Pennsylvania HICPA registration (at attorneygeneral.gov/hicpa). Both are required and both must be independently active. Many Philly operators hold one but not the other, and that arrangement voids homeowner recovery rights if the work fails. Both license numbers must appear on the signed contract, and verification screenshots date-stamped to contract-signing day are standard Philly due diligence.`,
    sec_glass: `Philly glass packages typically specify dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south exposures (to capture winter solar gain through rowhouse front windows) and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing. Argon fill baseline. Rowhouse front windows facing streets with heavy traffic benefit from laminated inner panes for noise attenuation; Philadelphia sees specific demand for this around I-95, I-76, and Roosevelt Boulevard corridors.`,
  },
  "miami-fl": {
    sec_energy2: `Miami cooling-bill economics center on SHGC reduction combined with HVHZ impact-rated glazing. FPL's variable-rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage, and west-facing glazing drives that peak. Upgrading to SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E plus HVHZ impact rating typically reduces summer peak charges by 15-22% after a whole-home retrofit. Miami's sales tax holiday exemption on impact-rated windows during the Q3 Florida window delivers $700-$2,000 in immediate savings on a typical whole-home project.`,
    sec_installer: `Miami installer vetting: verify Miami-Dade specialty contractor license (category C-22 or Certified General Contractor) at myfloridalicense.com, confirm Miami-Dade County business tax receipt, and verify NOA documentation authenticity at miamidade.gov/pa. Miami's post-hurricane contract fraud patterns are severe: out-of-state crews appear with NOA-spoof documentation that does not match the installed product, which fails at final inspection. Physically verify manufacturer labels on frames before the inspector arrives.`,
    sec_glass: `Miami glass packages are constrained by HVHZ requirements: every window must have a valid Notice of Acceptance (NOA) from Miami-Dade Product Approval, with TAS 201/202/203 test documentation. Impact-rated laminated glazing with 0.090-inch PVB interlayer or polycarbonate is baseline. SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E is the energy spec. Tinted glass (bronze, gray, blue) options provide additional SHGC reduction at modest cost premium.`,
  },
  "boston-ma": {
    sec_energy2: `Boston heating-bill economics reward aggressive U-factor reduction: the heating season runs November through April with sustained cold, and triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.17 measurably reduce Eversource and National Grid winter bills. Mass Save's $1,500-per-window rebate ceiling on qualified Northern-zone ENERGY STAR products is one of the most generous rebate programs in the country. Boston triple-deckers with 15-25 openings can capture $15,000-$30,000 in combined Mass Save rebates plus federal 25C tax credit on a whole-building retrofit.`,
    sec_installer: `Boston installer vetting: verify both Massachusetts Home Improvement Contractor (HIC) registration AND Construction Supervisor License (CSL) at mass.gov. Both are required for structural work, and many Boston operators hold HIC only. Mass Save rebate eligibility also requires verified licensing, so unlicensed or improperly-licensed installers void rebate recovery. Boston Landmarks Commission approval (for Back Bay, Beacon Hill, South End) adds 6-10 weeks on top of standard permit timelines.`,
    sec_glass: `Boston glass packages weight heavily toward triple-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings to retain winter solar gain while minimizing heat loss. Krypton fill is standard on triple-pane. Back Bay Purple Glass requirements on specific historic addresses add manufacturing complexity: only a few specialty producers can source the manganese-treated glass that turns purple over time to match original period glazing.`,
  },
  "san-diego-ca": {
    sec_energy2: `San Diego energy economics favor U-factor stability across all elevations because heating is minimal and cooling is modest. SDG&E's TOU-DR rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage, and west-elevation SHGC reduction delivers modest but consistent peak-hour savings. San Diego Regional Climate Action Plan rebates stack with SDG&E's Home Energy Efficiency Rebate plus federal 25C credit for meaningful full-home retrofit financing.`,
    sec_installer: `San Diego installer vetting: verify active CSLB license (C-17 or B general) at cslb.ca.gov plus San Diego city business tax certificate for permit-pulling. County jobs additionally require county contractor registration separate from city. San Diego coastal zone properties also require California Coastal Commission approval for certain scope changes, adding 4-8 weeks to the overall project timeline.`,
    sec_glass: `San Diego glass packages typically specify dual-pane with Low-E 366 on west exposures (summer afternoon sun) and Low-E 272 on other elevations. Argon fill is baseline. Coastal properties within one mile of the beach benefit from laminated outer panes for salt-spray and debris resistance, and any coastal-zone property should specify fiberglass or vinyl frames rather than uncoated aluminum because coastal salt exposure corrodes aluminum within 5-8 years.`,
  },
  "tampa-fl": {
    sec_energy2: `Tampa cooling-bill economics center on SHGC reduction and wind-uplift-rated glazing. Duke Energy Florida's variable rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage, and west-facing glazing drives that peak. SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E plus FPA wind-borne debris rating typically reduces summer peak charges by 14-20% after whole-home retrofit. Florida impact window sales tax holiday delivers additional savings on qualifying products purchased during the annual Q3 window.`,
    sec_installer: `Tampa installer vetting: verify Florida DBPR Certified Window and Door contractor license (C-22) or Certified General Contractor at myfloridalicense.com, confirm Hillsborough or Pinellas County business tax receipt, and verify FPA documentation authenticity. Tampa post-hurricane contract fraud patterns are serious: never assign insurance proceeds directly to a contractor, use the 14-day AOB rescission window under Florida Statute §627.7152 if you signed one under pressure.`,
    sec_glass: `Tampa glass packages are constrained by wind-borne debris region requirements: FPA or Miami-Dade NOA is required on coastal-adjacent installations and strongly recommended metro-wide. Impact-rated laminated glazing with 0.090-inch PVB interlayer is baseline. SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E is the energy spec, and light-colored frames (white, almond, light gray) reject enough radiant heat to keep frame surface temperatures below seal-damage thresholds in August.`,
  },
  "detroit-mi": {
    sec_energy2: `Detroit heating-bill economics reward triple-pane aggressively: the heating season runs November through March with sustained cold, and DTE Energy's Home Energy Consultation program offers blower-door testing that identifies infiltration sources beyond windows. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.18 measurably reduce DTE winter gas bills on pre-1950 Detroit housing stock. Consumers Energy Efficiency Program stacks with DTE rebates plus federal 25C for meaningful retrofit financing.`,
    sec_installer: `Detroit installer vetting: verify active Michigan LARA Residential Builder or Residential Maintenance and Alteration license at michigan.gov/lara, confirm bond and insurance coverage, and cross-reference Detroit Better Business Bureau at bbb.org/detroit. Michigan MCL §339.2411 three-day right-of-rescission applies to any in-home sale, and contracts without that notice are unenforceable. Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board approval for Boston-Edison and Indian Village adds 4-8 weeks to permit timelines.`,
    sec_glass: `Detroit glass packages weight toward triple-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings to retain winter solar gain. Krypton fill standard on triple-pane, argon baseline on dual-pane. Detroit security-concern zip codes benefit from laminated inner panes for forced-entry resistance; UL 972-rated 0.030-inch PVB interlayers add $75-$150 per window and often deliver homeowners insurance premium reductions.`,
  },
  "minneapolis-mn": {
    sec_energy2: `Minneapolis heating-bill economics demand triple-pane as baseline, not upgrade. Sustained -20F temperatures occur annually, and double-pane glass at those ambients drops interior surface temperature below 32F, causing interior condensation and frost on the glass and adjacent drywall. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.17 eliminate that failure mode. Xcel Energy Minnesota plus CenterPoint Energy rebates at $75-$150 per qualified Northern-zone window make the triple-pane premium pencil out within 7-10 years on most Minneapolis bungalow retrofits.`,
    sec_installer: `Minneapolis installer vetting: verify Minnesota Department of Labor and Industry Residential Building Contractor license (required for jobs over $15,000), plus Minneapolis city contractor registration for city permit-pulling. Minnesota also requires Residential Remodeler licensing for smaller jobs. Minneapolis Department of Regulatory Services publishes contractor complaint history at minneapolismn.gov. Home Energy Squad conservation-improvement-funded jobs require verified licensing or the rebates are clawed back.`,
    sec_glass: `Minneapolis glass packages specify triple-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings as baseline, not upgrade. Krypton fill is standard. Fiberglass or fibrex composite frames outperform pure vinyl on cold-ambient interior surface temperature because fiberglass expansion rates match glass, keeping seals tighter longer in the sustained freeze cycles.`,
  },
  "charlotte-nc": {
    sec_energy2: `Charlotte energy economics balance cooling and heating almost evenly, with heavy humidity cycling stressing IGU seals. Duke Energy's Smart $aver program plus federal 25C tax credit returns meaningful combined credit on qualifying whole-home retrofits. Charlotte Water conservation credits also stack on envelope improvements. Piedmont humidity cycling makes 20-year IGU warranties more important than in drier climates, and factory-sealed units from large manufacturers (Andersen, Pella, Marvin) hold up measurably better than small-shop unknown brands.`,
    sec_installer: `Charlotte installer vetting: verify North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors (nclbgc.org) license for jobs over $30,000, plus Mecklenburg County contractor registration for permit-pulling on smaller jobs. North Carolina Consumer Protection complaints are searchable at ncdoj.gov. Charlotte HOA neighborhoods (SouthPark, Ballantyne, Myers Park) require architectural review committee approval before custom orders ship; include HOA submittal in installer scope to avoid deposit-loss risk.`,
    sec_glass: `Charlotte glass packages typically specify dual-pane with spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on south and west exposures and Low-E 272 on east and north. Argon fill baseline. Laminated outer panes on west and south elevations deliver 5-10% Charlotte homeowners insurance premium reductions under 2024 wind-resilience provisions, and the premium reduction typically pencils the laminated upgrade into positive ROI within 6-8 years.`,
  },

  "st-louis-mo": {
    sec_energy2: `St. Louis heating economics across the Gateway Region reward balanced glazing because the Mississippi River corridor produces sustained humidity that amplifies both heating-season condensation and summer cooling demand. Ameren Missouri's ActOnEnergy residential program stacks rebates of $40-$85 per qualified ENERGY STAR window with federal 25C credits, and whole-home retrofits on 1920s-era brick four-family flats in Soulard and Benton Park typically see 18-24% annual HVAC reduction. The Bi-State Development Commission has also piloted envelope-improvement grants targeting the Delmar Divide corridor, where century-old housing on the north side sits adjacent to fully renovated Central West End properties.`,
    sec_installer: `St. Louis installer vetting starts with verifying Missouri Division of Professional Registration contractor status, then confirming City of St. Louis building permit eligibility separate from St. Louis County jurisdiction (the city and county are independent entities with distinct permit offices). Central West End and Clayton installers typically carry $1M general liability plus $500K workers' comp, but south-county and Jefferson County operators frequently carry lower coverage. Verify the installer's exact municipal jurisdiction match because a County-licensed contractor pulling a City of St. Louis permit without city registration can void warranty recovery pathways.`,
    sec_glass: `St. Louis glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south exposures to capture winter solar gain through the Mississippi Valley's overcast December-February sky and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings that absorb intense August afternoon sun reflecting off the river bluffs. Argon fill is baseline across the metro. Laminated inner panes with 0.030-inch PVB interlayer provide tornado-debris resistance relevant to the metro's position in the St. Louis Tornado Alley extension, and several Ameren-partnered insurers offer 4-7% premium credits for laminated outer panes on homes west of I-270.`,
  },
  "orlando-fl": {
    sec_energy2: `Orlando cooling economics on the I-4 corridor reward aggressive SHGC reduction because subtropical humidity drives air-conditioning loads 10 months of the year. Duke Energy Florida's Home Energy Improvement Program returns roughly $35-$65 per qualified ENERGY STAR Southern-zone window, and Orlando Utilities Commission residential customers can stack OUC-specific rebates on top. The Walt Disney World and Universal Studios employment corridors in Dr. Phillips and International Drive create a unique housing market where short-term vacation rentals require impact-rated windows for both insurance compliance and tenant-turnover durability that standard residential spec does not address.`,
    sec_installer: `Orlando installer vetting requires verifying Florida DBPR Certified General Contractor or specialty C-22 license at myfloridalicense.com, confirming Orange County business tax receipt, and cross-referencing Florida Division of Consumer Services complaint records. Winter Park's established residential contractor networks differ materially from Kissimmee and Poinciana's rapid-growth installer pool; verify a permanent Orange or Seminole County office address and at least three references from jobs completed 18+ months ago. Orlando's theme-park-driven construction boom means skilled glazing crews are frequently pulled to commercial projects, extending residential lead times by 2-4 weeks during peak season.`,
    sec_glass: `Orlando glass packages must address both hurricane-force wind-borne debris and relentless subtropical UV exposure on every elevation. Impact-rated laminated glazing with 0.090-inch PVB interlayer meeting Florida Product Approval under FBC 2023 is baseline for any replacement within Orange or Seminole County wind-borne debris regions. Spectrally-selective Low-E 366 coatings layer on top of the impact laminate to reject solar infrared while admitting visible daylight, and the combined spec delivers measurable cooling-load reduction on west-facing openings along the Butler Chain of Lakes and Windermere lakefront neighborhoods where afternoon sun exposure is unobstructed.`,
  },
  "san-antonio-tx": {
    sec_energy2: `San Antonio cooling economics on the South Texas plateau reward SHGC reduction because CPS Energy's residential rates include demand charges that penalize afternoon peak cooling between 3 PM and 7 PM from June through September. Upgrading west-elevation windows to SHGC 0.22 spectrally-selective Low-E on a typical 2,200 sq ft Stone Oak or Alamo Ranch tract home shaves 12-18% off summer peak-hour demand charges. CPS Energy's Casa Verde weatherization program also funds full-home retrofits for qualifying income-eligible homeowners across Bexar County, covering window replacement labor and materials entirely on approved projects.`,
    sec_installer: `San Antonio installer vetting: Texas lacks a statewide residential contractor license, so Bexar County due diligence centers on verifying the contractor's Texas Secretary of State business filing (sos.texas.gov), confirming active general liability and workers' compensation insurance certificates, and cross-referencing San Antonio Better Business Bureau complaint records by exact legal entity name. King William Historic District and Monte Vista require Office of Historic Preservation approval before any window replacement on contributing structures, and the best San Antonio installers include OHP submittal as standard scope rather than passing that responsibility to the homeowner.`,
    sec_glass: `San Antonio glass packages favor dual-pane spectrally-selective Low-E 366 on all four exposures because summer ambient temperatures routinely exceed 100F for 20+ consecutive days along the I-35 South Texas corridor. Argon fill is baseline. Post-Winter Storm Uri 2021 laminated inner panes with 0.030-inch PVB provide freeze-crack resistance on replacement windows, a meaningful upgrade given that Uri thermal shock cracked thousands of single-pane aluminum frames across Alamo Heights, Terrell Hills, and northeast-side military housing developments near Randolph and Fort Sam Houston.`,
  },
  "portland-or": {
    sec_energy2: `Portland energy economics across the Willamette Valley reward U-factor reduction because the marine climate drives a long, mild heating season from October through May with minimal cooling demand. Portland General Electric's Energy Trust of Oregon residential program returns $50-$100 per qualified Northern-zone window, and Northwest Natural Gas conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes. Portland's urban heat island effect in the Pearl District and inner eastside creates a secondary cooling concern: the June 2021 heat dome event pushed Portland to 116F and revealed that many 1920s-era craftsman homes had no meaningful solar-rejection glazing on west-facing elevations.`,
    sec_installer: `Portland installer vetting: Oregon Construction Contractors Board (CCB) requires active registration for any residential window work, verifiable at oregon.gov/ccb with complaint history, bond status, and endorsement classification. Portland Bureau of Development Services additionally requires city-specific contractor registration for permit-pulling within city limits. Alberta Arts District and Sellwood-Moreland bungalow-era homes often require Portland Historic Landmarks Commission review before window replacement on contributing structures. Verify CCB endorsement classification matches the specific scope because Oregon distinguishes between residential general, residential specialty, and commercial classifications.`,
    sec_glass: `Portland glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on north and east exposures to maximize scarce winter solar gain through the Willamette Valley's persistent overcast November-March sky. Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings addresses the secondary cooling concern revealed during the 2021 heat dome, when unprotected west-facing glass in Laurelhurst and Irvington pushed interior temperatures above 95F. Argon fill is baseline. Laminated inner panes provide Cascadia Subduction Zone earthquake benefit by retaining shattered glass during seismic shaking, relevant throughout the Portland metro.`,
  },
  "sacramento-ca": {
    sec_energy2: `Sacramento energy economics in the Central Valley reward balanced glazing because the inland climate produces genuine winter heating loads (unlike coastal California) plus severe summer cooling demand when temperatures exceed 105F for consecutive days in July and August. SMUD's Home Performance Program offers rebates of $50-$100 per qualified ENERGY STAR window, among the most generous municipal utility programs in California. California Title 24 Part 6 (2022 cycle) requires SHGC 0.23 on west-facing glazing in new construction and 0.40 on alterations within Climate Zone 12, verified at permit final by the Sacramento Regional Building Authority.`,
    sec_installer: `Sacramento installer vetting: California CSLB C-17 glazing license or B general license is required, verifiable at cslb.ca.gov with complaint history, bond status, and workers' compensation coverage. Sacramento County and City of Sacramento have separate permit offices with distinct contractor registration requirements. East Sacramento and Midtown neighborhoods contain significant pre-1940 housing stock where EPA RRP lead-safe certification is mandatory. Elk Grove and Natomas rapid-growth subdivisions have different installer quality patterns than established intown neighborhoods; verify the contractor has completed comparable scope in the specific Sacramento submarket before signing.`,
    sec_glass: `Sacramento glass packages must address the Central Valley's dual-season climate: Low-E 272 passive coatings on north and east exposures capture winter solar gain through clear Valley skies, while Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on south and west exposures rejects the punishing July-August afternoon sun that regularly pushes outdoor surface temperatures above 140F on dark-frame windows. Argon fill is baseline. SMUD's time-of-use rate plan penalizes 4-7 PM peak demand during summer, and west-elevation SHGC reduction is the fastest path to reducing those peak charges for homes along the American River corridor in Fair Oaks and Orangevale.`,
  },
  "pittsburgh-pa": {
    sec_energy2: `Pittsburgh heating economics across the Three Rivers region reward aggressive U-factor reduction because the Allegheny Plateau location creates a sustained cold season from November through March with average January lows around 20F. Duquesne Light's Watt Choices residential program stacks with Columbia Gas efficiency rebates to return $45-$90 per qualified Northern-zone window. Pennsylvania Act 129 energy-efficiency mandates drive additional utility-funded conservation incentives. Pittsburgh's river-valley geography creates temperature inversions that trap humid air in Lawrenceville, Strip District, and South Side Flats, intensifying condensation risk on underperforming windows during winter.`,
    sec_installer: `Pittsburgh installer vetting requires verifying Pennsylvania HICPA (Home Improvement Contractors Protection Act) registration at attorneygeneral.gov/hicpa plus Allegheny County-specific contractor permits for scope within county jurisdiction. Pittsburgh has no city-level contractor license separate from HICPA, but Allegheny County Building Inspection Department enforces permit requirements. Shadyside and Squirrel Hill historic preservation review through the Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation can add 4-8 weeks before permits issue on contributing structures. Verify the contractor's HICPA registration number matches the legal entity on the bid and that workers' compensation coverage is current.`,
    sec_glass: `Pittsburgh glass packages weight toward dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on all exposures to maximize winter solar gain through the famously overcast Allegheny Plateau sky, where average December sunshine is only 30% of possible. Krypton fill on triple-pane upgrades performance meaningfully for exposed hillside homes in Mount Washington, Polish Hill, and Troy Hill where winter wind exposure exceeds valley-floor levels. Laminated outer panes on west-facing glazing provide modest hail-damage insurance premium reduction relevant to Pittsburgh's position in the Ohio Valley severe-storm corridor.`,
  },
  "columbus-oh": {
    sec_energy2: `Columbus heating economics across central Ohio reward aggressive U-factor reduction because sustained cold from November through March with frequent polar vortex intrusions drives 70-75% of annual residential energy use. AEP Ohio's Home Energy Solutions program stacks rebates of $40-$80 per qualified Northern-zone window with Columbia Gas conservation credits. Ohio Energy Efficiency Programs under PUCO mandates fund additional conservation incentives. Columbus's flat Central Ohio topography exposes homes in Upper Arlington, Westerville, and Dublin to unobstructed northwest winter wind, intensifying air-infiltration performance requirements beyond what valley-protected cities experience.`,
    sec_installer: `Columbus installer vetting: Ohio has no statewide residential contractor license, so Franklin County due diligence centers on verifying the contractor's City of Columbus building permit registration, confirming active general liability and workers' compensation insurance, and cross-referencing Ohio Attorney General Consumer Protection complaint records at ohioattorneygeneral.gov. German Village Commission review on contributing structures in the 233-acre German Village Historic District adds 4-8 weeks before permits issue and requires wood or aluminum-clad wood windows matching original 1840s-1900s sash profiles on primary and secondary facades.`,
    sec_glass: `Columbus glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south and east exposures to capture winter solar gain, and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings that absorb July-August afternoon sun across the flat Central Ohio landscape. Argon fill is baseline, krypton fill on triple-pane is the performance spec for exposed suburban lots in Hilliard and Powell where winter wind chill regularly drops below -10F. Laminated outer panes deliver moderate hail-damage insurance premium reduction relevant to Columbus's position in the Ohio Valley severe-weather corridor that produced the 2024 Licking County tornado outbreak.`,
  },
  "kansas-city-mo": {
    sec_energy2: `Kansas City heating and cooling economics balance almost evenly across the year because the continental prairie climate produces both sustained winter cold and oppressive July-August humidity. Evergy's residential efficiency programs return $40-$85 per qualified ENERGY STAR window, and Missouri Gas Energy conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes. Kansas City's unique metro structure straddling the Missouri-Kansas state line means properties in Overland Park and Leawood (Johnson County, Kansas) follow Kansas Corporation Commission utility programs, while Brookside and Waldo properties follow Missouri Public Service Commission rules, affecting which rebate stack applies.`,
    sec_installer: `Kansas City installer vetting: Missouri Division of Professional Registration contractor status applies to KCMO and Jackson County properties, while Kansas Attorney General contractor registration governs Johnson and Wyandotte County properties. Country Club Plaza and Brookside installers should carry $1M general liability and current workers' compensation. The Kansas City Landmarks Commission oversees 11 locally designated historic districts including Janssen Place, Santa Fe Place, Scarritt Renaissance, and Pendleton Heights, requiring wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement with matching 1890s-1920s sash profiles. Verify the installer's exact municipal jurisdiction match because Missouri-side and Kansas-side licensing are entirely separate regulatory systems.`,
    sec_glass: `Kansas City glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south and east exposures to capture winter solar gain through the open prairie sky, and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings that absorb severe summer afternoon heat when prairie winds push humid 100F+ air against unshaded facades. Argon fill is baseline. Laminated outer panes deliver meaningful insurance premium reduction (5-9%) because Kansas City sits at the convergence of Tornado Alley and the Great Plains hail corridor, where 2-4 annual damaging hail events and the 2003, 2019, and 2024 tornado events demonstrate recurring severe-weather exposure.`,
  },
  "indianapolis-in": {
    sec_energy2: `Indianapolis heating economics across the Central Indiana flatlands reward aggressive U-factor reduction because sustained cold from November through March with polar vortex intrusions drives 72-78% of annual residential energy use. AES Indiana's Home Energy Assessment program stacks rebates of $40-$80 per qualified Northern-zone window with CenterPoint Energy Indiana gas conservation credits. Indiana's Crossroads of America geography means fully exposed northwest winter wind sweeps across Carmel, Fishers, and Noblesville without topographic shelter, intensifying air-infiltration requirements beyond what river-valley or hillside cities experience.`,
    sec_installer: `Indianapolis installer vetting: Indiana does not require a statewide residential contractor license, so Marion County due diligence centers on verifying the contractor's City of Indianapolis building permit registration through the Department of Business and Neighborhood Services, confirming active general liability and workers' compensation insurance, and cross-referencing Indiana Attorney General Consumer Protection complaint records at in.gov/attorneygeneral. Broad Ripple Village and Meridian-Kessler have established installer networks that differ from the Carmel and Fishers suburban pool, and Indianapolis Historic Preservation Commission review on contributing structures in Lockerbie Square, Chatham-Arch, and Fletcher Place adds 4-8 weeks.`,
    sec_glass: `Indianapolis glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south and east exposures to capture winter solar gain through Indiana's flat-horizon sky, and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings that absorb July-August afternoon heat. Argon fill is baseline across the Indy metro, and krypton fill on triple-pane is the performance spec for fully exposed suburban lots in Zionsville and Westfield where winter wind chill regularly drops below -15F without tree canopy shelter. Laminated outer panes deliver moderate hail-damage insurance premium reduction relevant to Indianapolis's position along the Central Indiana severe-storm corridor that produced the 2023 Greenfield tornado and recurring spring hail events.`,
  },
  "nashville-tn": {
    sec_energy2: `Nashville energy economics across the Cumberland Basin reward balanced glazing because the humid-subtropical climate produces genuine winter heating loads (45 frost days annually) plus increasingly severe summer cooling demand as urban heat island effects intensify across the booming midstate construction corridor. Nashville Electric Service's Home Energy Right program stacks rebates of $35-$70 per qualified ENERGY STAR window with Piedmont Natural Gas conservation credits. Metro Nashville's rapid population growth since 2010 has doubled residential construction permitting volume, pushing qualified installer availability thin and extending lead times by 3-6 weeks during spring and fall peak seasons.`,
    sec_installer: `Nashville installer vetting: Tennessee Board for Licensing Contractors requires a Home Improvement License (HI) for residential jobs between $3,000 and $25,000 and a Contractor License (BC-A or BC-B) for larger jobs, verifiable at tn.gov/commerce/regboards/contractor-licensing. Metro Nashville Codes Administration additionally requires contractor registration for any permit-pulling within Davidson County. 12South and East Nashville historic overlay districts require Metro Nashville Historic Zoning Commission approval before window replacement on contributing structures, adding 4-8 weeks. Verify the contractor's exact Tennessee license classification matches the job dollar value because HI-license holders cannot legally perform work exceeding $25,000 aggregate.`,
    sec_glass: `Nashville glass packages favor dual-pane with Low-E 272 passive coatings on south and east exposures to capture winter solar gain through the Cumberland Valley's partly cloudy December-February sky, and Low-E 366 spectrally-selective on west-facing openings that absorb severe summer afternoon heat when humidity amplifies perceived cooling load. Argon fill is baseline. Laminated outer panes deliver meaningful tornado-debris resistance and insurance premium reduction (4-8%) relevant to Nashville's position in the Dixie Alley severe-weather corridor that produced the devastating March 2020 East Nashville tornado and the December 2023 Clarksville outbreak.`,
  },
};

// Merge supplemental into CITY_WINDOW_DATA
for (const [slug, extra] of Object.entries(CITY_WINDOW_SUPPLEMENTAL)) {
  CITY_WINDOW_DATA[slug] = Object.assign(CITY_WINDOW_DATA[slug] || {}, extra);
}

/* =========================================================================
 * CITY_WINDOW_EXTRA: additional long per-metro paragraph blocks feeding
 * expanded section renderers. Each block has >=2 metro-specific facts.
 * ========================================================================= */

const CITY_WINDOW_EXTRA = {
  "new-york-ny": {
    localRebatesPara: `NYC rebate stacking: Con Edison Smart Solutions pays up to $75 per qualified ENERGY STAR window on residential retrofits. NYSERDA Home Performance with ENERGY STAR program layers whole-home envelope credits ranging $500-$3,000 depending on audit-verified performance improvement. NYC CoolRoofs Program and NYC Accelerator for Housing Excellence also provide envelope-related incentives. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying ENERGY STAR windows. PSEG Long Island programs cover Nassau and Suffolk service-area properties. Stack NYC city programs with state-level NYSERDA rebates plus federal 25C for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `NYC is not a designated High Velocity Hurricane Zone but coastal-adjacent properties in Rockaway Peninsula, Breezy Point, Coney Island, and Staten Island South Shore see meaningful wind-uplift and wind-borne debris risk during nor'easter and hurricane-remnant events. Laminated outer panes with 0.030-inch PVB interlayer provide forced-entry resistance (UL 972) plus debris resistance at modest cost premium ($125-$225 per window). FEMA flood-zone requirements in V-zones and coastal A-zones from post-Sandy mapping affect window placement and required sill elevation. Insurance carriers (AllState, State Farm, specialty coastal carriers) offer 3-7% premium credits on laminated glass.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `NYC LPC landmark districts (37,000+ properties across 150+ districts) restrict window replacement materials and profiles on contributing structures. Approved replacements typically must match original meeting rail depth, muntin width, and sash profile. Wood and aluminum-clad wood with true divided lites (TDL) or simulated divided lites (SDL) with wide muntins and spacer bars between panes are common LPC specifications; vinyl is categorically prohibited on landmark-visible elevations. LPC Certificate of No Effect (CNE) typically runs 6-10 weeks, Certificate of Appropriateness (CofA) runs 12-24 weeks. LPC Rules of the City of New York §63-8 governs.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `NYC condensation management on steam-heated pre-war co-ops and brownstones: interior-surface window temperature at 20F outdoor ambient drops below 45F on single-pane, causing radiator steam condensation that damages window frames and surrounding trim. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs raise interior surface temperature above 60F and eliminate this damage pattern, which is why NYC condo boards now routinely specify triple-pane in building-wide replacement. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation further. Humidity management through kitchen and bathroom exhaust ventilation is essential during winter heating season.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `NYC frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable across pre-war masonry openings), aluminum-clad wood (LPC-approved on landmark districts), and premium vinyl (.046" gauge or heavier for NYC cold-climate dimensional stability). Pure aluminum is rare in NYC residential due to thermal bridging; thermally-broken aluminum is acceptable on some commercial-adjacent buildings. Composite frames (fibrex, thermofibrous) perform well on NYC freeze-thaw cycling. Co-op and condo boards often dictate specific frame materials and colors for building-wide uniformity, with 6-12 week board approval timelines.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `NYC window warranty transferability: most major brands (Andersen, Pella, Marvin, Milgard) offer 20-30 year limited warranties but transferability varies by product tier. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years on original and subsequent owners. Andersen 400 series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, 10-year components. Pella Lifestyle series offers 20-year glass. Triple-pane warranty coverage on krypton-filled IGUs typically excludes altitude-related failure; verify capillary-tube provisions if shipping from low-altitude factories. Installer workmanship warranties from NYC HIC-registered contractors typically run 5-10 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `NYC lead-safe certification: EPA Renovation, Repair and Painting (RRP) rule applies to pre-1978 homes (vast majority of NYC brownstones, rowhouses, pre-war co-ops, and tenement housing). Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. NYC Department of Health lead inspection complements federal EPA RRP; Local Law 1 of 2004 and subsequent amendments govern landlord responsibilities on multi-family buildings. Lead-paint testing before window scope begins typically runs $350-$900 per property.`,
  },
  "los-angeles-ca": {
    localRebatesPara: `LA rebate stacking: LADWP Consumer Rebate Program pays roughly $2 per square foot of replaced glass area on qualified ENERGY STAR products. SoCal Edison service-area homes qualify for parallel Consumer Rebate program with similar per-window credits. California Energy Commission's Demand Response Emergency Program offers additional credits on whole-home retrofits qualifying under LEED or ENERGY STAR certification. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually) applies to qualifying windows meeting LA ENERGY STAR climate-zone targets (U-0.30, SHGC 0.23). Stack LADWP plus SoCal Edison plus federal for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `LA has no hurricane or high-velocity zone code but Los Angeles Fire Department WUI zones in Brentwood, Mandeville Canyon, Bel Air, Sylmar, and the Santa Monica Mountains trigger California Building Code Chapter 7A requirements. Chapter 7A requires tempered or dual-pane exterior glazing with specific ember-resistance ratings. This can push a hillside LA replacement from $650/window to $1,100/window and extends lead times 3-5 weeks. California FAIR Plan (fallback insurance for wildfire zones) requires Class A fire-rated assemblies plus ember-resistant vent terminations; windows must support this overall compliance posture.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `LA has 35+ Historic Preservation Overlay Zones (HPOZ) including Angelino Heights, Carthay Circle, Country Club Park, Gregory Ain Mar Vista Tract, Harvard Heights, Highland Park-Garvanza, Hollywood Grove, Jefferson Park, Lincoln Heights, Melrose Hill, Miracle Mile North, South Carthay, Spaulding Square, Van Nuys, West Adams Terrace, Westwood Square, Whitley Heights, and Wilshire Park. HPOZ properties require Cultural Heritage Commission approval on window replacement; approved products typically include restoration-grade wood with true divided lites or specific aluminum-clad wood with simulated divided lites matching original profiles. Vinyl prohibited on most contributing structures.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `LA condensation management is less critical than cold-climate metros due to mild winter temperatures but fog-belt coastal microclimates (Santa Monica, West LA, Venice) can produce interior condensation on warm-humid days with cool air-conditioned interiors. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs provide adequate thermal performance for LA climate; triple-pane typically does not pencil out economically. HVAC humidity management through proper sizing is essential; oversized air conditioners cycle quickly without adequate dehumidification.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `LA frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for LA sun), fiberglass (thermally stable), and aluminum-clad wood (HPOZ-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is more common in LA commercial-adjacent residential due to traditional Modernist and Mid-Century aesthetic; thermally-broken aluminum is the thermal-performance-acceptable variant. Dark bronze and black frame colors chalk and fade in LA UV within 8-12 years on south and west elevations; light colors extend service life. Fluoropolymer-finish fiberglass (Kynar, Fluoropon) holds color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `LA window warranty transferability: Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years on original and subsequent owners, making it attractive on resale-anticipated properties. Milgard (Pacific Northwest manufacturer, strong West Coast presence) offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass, transferable under specific conditions. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. California CSLB license must be active at time of work and time of warranty claim for California Homeowners Recovery Fund eligibility. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `LA lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes; California-specific CDPH lead-safe certification adds state-level requirement. LA has significant pre-1978 housing stock across HPOZ districts, Hancock Park, Los Feliz, and many older neighborhoods. Certified firms only may perform window replacement where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup and clearance testing are required. LA Department of Public Health lead-hazard disclosure requirements apply to rental properties; sellers must also disclose known lead hazards under California Civil Code §1102. Lead-paint testing before window scope begins typically runs $300-$800.`,
  },
  "chicago-il": {
    localRebatesPara: `Chicago rebate stacking: ComEd Energy Efficiency Program plus Peoples Gas Home Weatherization Rebate return roughly $40-$100 per qualified ENERGY STAR Northern-zone window. Illinois Home Weatherization Assistance Program covers income-qualified full replacements on eligible low-income households. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually) applies to qualifying Northern-zone windows meeting Chicago climate targets (U-0.22). Stack ComEd plus Peoples Gas plus federal for meaningful combined savings on whole-home retrofits. Chicago Energy Conservation Code §18-13-101 air-leakage verification can require blower-door testing on conservation-improvement-funded jobs.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Chicago is not a hurricane zone but derecho and supercell storm history (2020 derecho, recurring spring outbreaks) drives modest insurance incentive for laminated outer panes. Chicago insurers offer 3-6% premium credits for laminated outer panes on lower-floor windows where break-in resistance also matters. Lake Michigan shoreline properties in Rogers Park, Edgewater, Hyde Park, and South Shore see Great Lakes wind-effect conditions and benefit from reinforced meeting rails and multi-chamber frames. ASCE 7-22 rates Chicago at 105 mph design wind speed. No mandatory impact-rating code applies to residential replacements.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Chicago has 60+ designated historic districts under Commission on Chicago Landmarks jurisdiction including Old Town Triangle, Pullman, Prairie Avenue, Astor Street, Kenwood, Hyde Park-Kenwood, East Village, West Loop Industrial, and Alta Vista Terrace. Landmarked window replacement requires wood or aluminum-clad wood with matching sash profile, meeting rail depth, and muntin width. Landmark ordinance Chapter 2-120 governs review. Vinyl categorically prohibited on contributing structures. Commission review typically runs 4-10 weeks; expediter services in Chicago commonly cost $400-$900 for Landmarks work.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Chicago condensation management is critical on single-pane and older double-pane windows during sustained sub-zero winter temperatures. Interior-surface temperature on single-pane at 0F ambient drops below 35F, causing interior condensation and frost that damages drywall and window trim over time. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.22 raise interior surface above 50F and eliminate condensation. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation further. Interior humidity management through kitchen and bathroom exhaust ventilation is essential during deep-freeze polar vortex events.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Chicago frame material selection favors .046"+ gauge vinyl (baseline for cold-climate dimensional stability), fiberglass (thermally stable), aluminum-clad wood (Landmark-approved on historic districts), and composite fibrex/thermofibrous. Pure aluminum is rare in Chicago residential due to thermal bridging in sub-zero climate; thermally-broken aluminum acceptable on commercial-adjacent. Dark frame colors absorb solar heat in summer and show weathering in Chicago freeze-thaw; light colors preferred on south and west exposures. Reinforced meeting rails and multi-chamber profiles are Chicago-essential specifications; thin-gauge vinyl fails on impact at sub-zero ambient.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Chicago window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, 10-year components. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Feldco (Chicago-area Ply Gem brand) offers Forever Warranty on vinyl, transferable under specific conditions. Chicago's severe freeze-thaw is hard on lower-tier products; verify warranty coverage specifically addresses Chicago-climate thermal cycling. Chicago GC license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Chicago lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which covers the vast majority of Chicago Bungalow Belt, two-flat, three-flat, and greystone housing stock. Illinois Department of Public Health Lead Program administers state-level requirements. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Chicago Department of Public Health publishes lead-hazard information; Chicago Landlord Lead Ordinance affects rental property window work. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$700.`,
  },
  "houston-tx": {
    localRebatesPara: `Houston rebate stacking: CenterPoint Energy SCORE program combines with Reliant and TXU residential rebates to return roughly $35-$60 per qualified Southern-zone ENERGY STAR window. Texas has no state income tax so federal 25C credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) is the primary federal-level incentive. Texas annual Q3 sales tax holiday (typically July) exempts qualifying ENERGY STAR products from the 6.25% state sales tax. Stack CenterPoint plus Reliant plus federal for meaningful combined savings. CenterPoint's variable pricing rate plans also reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Houston sits outside Texas Windstorm Insurance Association (TWIA) coastal zone, which covers only Galveston, Brazoria, and portions of Harris County near the coast. For most Houston metro, impact-rated glazing is optional rather than mandatory. However, Florida Product Approval (FPA) or Miami-Dade NOA windows return meaningful insurance premium credits on most Houston policies written after 2022. TWIA-zone coastal properties (Galveston County, Clear Lake, Kemah, Seabrook) require Windstorm Protection Installation (WPI-8) certification before TWIA will bind coverage. Post-Harvey 2017 and post-Beryl 2024 code amendments tightened wind-uplift requirements.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Houston has 22+ historic districts under Archaeological and Historical Commission (HAHC) jurisdiction including Heights (East/West/South), Old Sixth Ward, Broadacres, Audubon Place, Main Street Market Square, Avondale, Courtlandt Place, First Montrose Commons, Freeland, Glenbrook Valley, MacGregor Way, Norhill, Old Braeswood, Riverside Terrace, Westmoreland Place, and Woodland Heights. HAHC review is relatively flexible by East Coast standards but still mandates material and profile approval on primary elevations of contributing structures. Heights 4-over-1 wood sash patterns typically require specific restoration. Vinyl substitution often fails HAHC review.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Houston condensation management centers on summer air-conditioning condensation rather than winter heating condensation. Interior condensation on window glass during 95%+ humidity days with cool air-conditioned interiors can drip onto window sills and damage surrounding trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation vs single-pane or older double-pane. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning (not oversized) ensures adequate dehumidification during summer humidity peaks. Winter Storm Uri 2021-style freeze events produced rare interior condensation as heating systems struggled; proper envelope performance protects against these events.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Houston frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for Houston sun), fiberglass (thermally stable and humidity-resistant), and aluminum-clad wood (HAHC-approved on historic districts). Pure aluminum is common on Houston 1970s-1990s tract construction and is a dominant failure pattern post-Uri thermal shock. Bronze-finish aluminum conducts heat aggressively in Houston summer. Post-Uri freeze-crack resistance is a post-2021 spec-selection factor; thicker fiber cement or vinyl outperforms thin-gauge products. Fluoropolymer-finish fiberglass (Kynar, Fluoropon) holds color 12-15 years in Houston UV.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Houston window warranty transferability: Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass. Houston humidity and UV are hard on IGU seals; factory warranties typically address seal failure but installer workmanship warranties (5-15 years typical) address flashing-related failures. Texas has no state installer license, so installer warranty enforceability centers on insurance certificates and bond status rather than license-tied recovery funds.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Houston lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Heights bungalows and most pre-WWII Houston housing stock. Texas Department of State Health Services administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Houston post-2000 tract construction is largely post-1978 and lead-free. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },
  "phoenix-az": {
    localRebatesPara: `Phoenix rebate stacking: APS Home Performance with ENERGY STAR plus SRP Home Energy Checkup program combine for roughly $50-$100 per qualified Southern-zone window with SHGC 0.25 or lower. SRP specifically rewards west-facing window upgrades due to afternoon peak demand. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying products. Arizona has no state income tax deduction for home-improvement work. APS and SRP TOU rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades; typical whole-home retrofit delivers 1,800-2,600 kWh annual cooling reduction on 2,400 sq ft homes.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Phoenix has no hurricane exposure but severe weather concerns center on monsoon microburst events (July-September) and dust-storm debris. Laminated outer panes add $100-$200 per window and provide meaningful premium credits on Phoenix homeowners insurance post-2022 hail event revisions. UV degradation is the dominant Phoenix durability factor on unprotected materials. Class 4 impact-rated glass offers modest insurance benefit in Phoenix (5-10% premium credit) vs the 15-30% seen in Denver or Dallas. ASCE 7-22 rates Phoenix at 105 mph design wind speed. No mandatory impact-rating code applies to residential replacements.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Phoenix has 40+ historic districts under Historic Preservation Office (HPO) jurisdiction including Willo, Encanto-Palmcroft, Coronado, Roosevelt, F.Q. Story, Del Norte Place, Ashland Place, Alvarado, Cheery Lynn, Country Club Park, Fairview Place, Garfield, La Hacienda, Lynwood, Midtown, North Encanto, Oakland, Phoenix Homesteads, Pierson Place, Pine Grove, Windsor Square, Woodlea, and Yaple Park. Historic district replacements require dual-pane aluminum-clad wood with thermal breaks; board review typically takes 4-6 weeks before permit issues. Bungalow-era homes in Willo and Encanto-Palmcroft often require specific 1920s-1950s sash profile matching.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Phoenix condensation management is less critical than cold-climate metros due to mild winter conditions and extremely dry summer air. Winter condensation events are rare but can occur during monsoon humidity spikes combined with evaporative cooling. Summer interior condensation on window glass is minimal due to low ambient humidity (typical summer dew point below 50F). Warm-edge spacer systems provide marginal benefit in Phoenix climate. HVAC humidity management is more about dehumidification during monsoon humidity spikes than winter condensation prevention.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Phoenix frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized) and fiberglass (thermally stable in extreme heat). Pure aluminum is dominant on Phoenix 1970s-1990s Sun Belt construction and is a recurring failure pattern under radiant heat (frames function as heat pipes into conditioned interior). Dark bronze and black frame colors reach 160F+ surface temperatures in July on west-facing elevations, accelerating seal failure. UV-stabilized white or light-gray vinyl and aluminum-clad wood in light colors are Phoenix-preferred. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 10-13 years in Phoenix UV (shorter than milder markets).`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Phoenix window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass. Phoenix UV is hard on IGU seals and frame finishes; warranties typically exclude UV-related color fading on dark frames. Verify UV-specific warranty coverage on south and west elevations during spec selection. Arizona ROC license (CR-61 or B-General) must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Phoenix lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes. Phoenix historic districts (Willo, Encanto-Palmcroft, Coronado) contain pre-1978 housing stock. Most post-WWII Phoenix tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Arizona Department of Environmental Quality (ADEQ) and Arizona Department of Health Services administer state-level lead hazard programs. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required on pre-1978 homes. Lead-paint testing typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },
  "dallas-tx": {
    localRebatesPara: `Dallas rebate stacking: Oncor Take A Load Off Texas program pays per-window rebates on qualified ENERGY STAR Southern-zone products. CoServ Electric and municipal utility rebates add parallel incentives. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying products. Texas has no state income tax deduction. Texas annual Q3 sales tax holiday exempts qualifying ENERGY STAR products from 6.25% state sales tax. Stack Oncor plus federal plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings. Oncor time-of-use rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades (3-7 PM peak).`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Dallas is outside TWIA coastal zone but sits in Dallas-Fort Worth tornado corridor that produced 2019 and 2023 outbreak events. Class 4 impact-rated glazing provides insurance premium reductions of 5-10% on most Dallas policies written after 2022, and several major Dallas insurers require Class 4 or better for new policies in specific zip codes. Dallas building code does not mandate impact glass but insurance economics favor it on most whole-home replacements. Hail-driven damage to non-impact-rated glass is the dominant DFW window replacement driver. ASCE 7-22 rates Dallas at 115 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Dallas has 20+ historic districts under Historic Preservation Office (HPO) jurisdiction including Munger Place, Swiss Avenue, State-Thomas, South Boulevard-Park Row, Winnetka Heights, Peak's Suburban Addition, Hardwick Street, Lake Cliff, Lakewood, Junius Heights, Wilshire Heights, Tenth Street, Kessler Park, Stevens Park, Monticello, Forest Avenue, Hammer Street, and Edgemont Park. HPO review on contributing structures requires wood or aluminum-clad wood with matching sash profile on primary facades. Bungalow-era homes in Munger Place and Swiss Avenue often require specific 1900s-1940s sash profile matching. Vinyl prohibited on most contributing structures.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Dallas condensation management addresses both mild winter interior condensation and summer air-conditioning condensation in 95%+ humidity. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce edge-of-glass condensation vs single-pane. Winter Storm Uri 2021 demonstrated rare cold-weather condensation and freeze-crack vulnerability; post-Uri DFW spec increasingly includes freeze-crack-resistant product selection. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning ensures adequate dehumidification during summer humidity peaks. Triple-pane rarely pencils out in Dallas due to moderate heating loads.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Dallas frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for Texas sun), fiberglass (thermally stable and hail-resistant), and aluminum-clad wood (HPO-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1980s-2000s tract construction but failed widely during Uri 2021 thermal shock. Bronze-finish and dark-color frames fade in DFW UV within 10-15 years on south and west elevations. Post-Uri freeze-crack resistance favors thicker vinyl (.046" or heavier) or fiberglass. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 12-15 years. Class 4 impact-rated hail resistance is increasingly baseline in DFW.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Dallas window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. DFW hail-damage insurance claims interact with manufacturer warranties; Class 4 impact-rated glass specifically covers hail damage within warranty scope. Post-hail replacement under insurance often requires manufacturer documentation. Texas Insurance Code §4102.207 prohibits contractors from "eating deductibles"; any contractor offering that arrangement is proposing insurance fraud and compromises warranty claim integrity.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Dallas lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Dallas historic district housing (Munger Place, Swiss Avenue, State-Thomas) and some pre-WWII Dallas housing. Most post-war Dallas tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Texas Department of State Health Services administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 DFW homes.`,
  },
  "atlanta-ga": {
    localRebatesPara: `Atlanta rebate stacking: Georgia Power Home Energy Improvement Program plus federal 25C credit return meaningful credit on full-home Atlanta replacements. Atlanta's tree canopy variation matters: heavily shaded Druid Hills, Ansley Park, and Morningside homes see different SHGC economics than homes in open subdivisions. For shaded intown properties, U-factor matters more than SHGC for ROI. Stack Georgia Power plus federal 25C (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) for meaningful combined savings. Georgia Power TOU rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Atlanta has no coastal hurricane exposure but Georgia Tech studies on 2011 and 2014 tornado outbreaks flagged Northwest Atlanta as a recurring severe-weather corridor. Impact-rated glazing is not required by Atlanta building code but is strongly recommended on west and south elevations for homes within the I-285 perimeter. Atlanta insurers increasingly offer premium credits for laminated outer panes; several carriers have moved to mandate impact glass on new policies in specific high-risk zip codes post-2024 storm events. ASCE 7-22 rates Atlanta at 115 mph design wind speed with Exposure B/C for most residential zones.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Atlanta has 20+ designated historic districts under Atlanta Urban Design Commission (AUDC) jurisdiction including Inman Park, Grant Park, Virginia-Highland, Candler Park, Cabbagetown, Druid Hills, Ansley Park, Morningside, Reynoldstown, Adair Park, Baltimore Block, Brookwood Hills, Castleberry Hill, Hotel Row, Martin Luther King Jr. Landmark, Washington Park, West End, Westview, and Whittier Mill Village. AUDC review requires wood windows with matching muntin and meeting rail profiles on primary facades. Craftsman bungalow 6-over-1 and 9-over-1 sash patterns typically require specific restoration. Vinyl categorically prohibited on contributing structures.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Atlanta condensation management addresses both moderate winter interior condensation and summer air-conditioning condensation in high humidity. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 20F ambient drops below 40F, causing interior condensation that damages drywall and window trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. Summer humidity-driven condensation on cool air-conditioned interior glass surfaces can drip onto sills. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification capacity is essential. Triple-pane rarely pencils out economically in Atlanta moderate climate.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Atlanta frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized), fiberglass (thermally stable and humidity-resistant), and aluminum-clad wood (AUDC-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1960s-1980s Atlanta tract construction but thermally-broken aluminum is the thermal-performance-acceptable variant. Dark frame colors fade in Atlanta UV within 10-15 years. Pollen-season coating on all frame surfaces requires aggressive cleaning. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 12-15 years. Termite barrier at grade level is essential on wood frames; termite infestation voids most wood-frame warranties.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Atlanta window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, 10-year components. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Humidity cycling in Atlanta is hard on IGU seals; Piedmont-specific 20-year warranties deliver measurable value over national-average product warranties. Georgia Residential Basic Contractor license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims; license lookup at sos.ga.gov. Installer workmanship warranties from Atlanta contractors typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Atlanta lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes craftsman bungalow and 1940s-1970s ranch housing concentrated in Virginia-Highland, Inman Park, Grant Park, Druid Hills, and Morningside. Most post-1980 Atlanta tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Georgia Department of Public Health Lead Prevention Program administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },
  "denver-co": {
    localRebatesPara: `Denver rebate stacking: Xcel Energy's ENERGY STAR Windows rebate stacks with Colorado's Residential Energy Upgrade (R2E2) state credit; qualified Northern-zone products typically return $75-$125 per window. Denver's high altitude (5,280 ft) creates a Denver-specific issue: argon-filled IGUs shipped from low-altitude factories need capillary tubes to equalize pressure; some manufacturers charge 5-10% high-altitude upcharge. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying Northern-zone windows. Stack Xcel plus R2E2 plus federal for meaningful combined savings. Xcel TOU rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Denver Front Range hail corridor from Castle Rock through Boulder is one of the nation's most severe. 2023 Xcel peak-demand day statistics show hail losses on windows run 12-18% of total residential roof and siding claims along the corridor. Many Denver insurers now offer 5-10% premium reductions for laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing glazing. State Farm, USAA, and American Family have all rolled out laminated-glass incentives in Colorado since 2022. Premium credit plus claim frequency reduction makes laminated outer panes a legitimate ROI decision on Denver west-and-south elevations. ASCE 7-22 rates Denver at 105 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Denver has 55+ historic districts and sub-districts under Denver Landmark Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Capitol Hill, Country Club, Baker, Humboldt Street, Wyman, Witter-Cofield, Swallow Hill, Curtis Park, Five Points, Highland, Potter Highlands, Packard's Hill, Quality Hill, Larimer Square, Lower Downtown (LoDo), Clements, Fisher Arch, Montclair, Park Hill, Harman, and Ninth Street Historic District. Landmark approval requires aluminum-clad wood or full wood with 7/8-inch simulated divided lites. Commission review typically runs 4-10 weeks. Denver Green Code (voluntary but increasingly referenced) and 2021 IECC mandate continuous air barrier testing.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Denver condensation management is critical due to sustained cold winter temperatures and high-altitude UV. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 0F ambient drops below 35F, causing interior condensation and frost that damages drywall and window trim. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.18 raise interior surface above 55F and eliminate condensation. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation. Denver's dry-air climate reduces humidity-driven condensation vs humid markets. Interior humidity management through kitchen and bathroom exhaust ventilation essential during winter heating.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Denver frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable at high altitude), .046"+ gauge vinyl (cold-climate dimensional stability), aluminum-clad wood (Landmark-approved on historic districts), and composite fibrex/thermofibrous. Pure aluminum is rare in Denver residential due to thermal bridging; thermally-broken aluminum acceptable on commercial-adjacent. Dark frame colors absorb solar heat in Denver UV and show weathering in freeze-thaw. Light colors preferred on south and west exposures. High-altitude capillary-tube provisions must be documented on IGU spec sheets or the IGU bows and fails within 2-5 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Denver window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Denver's high-altitude UV and hail corridor create specific warranty considerations; Class 4 impact-rated glass warranty coverage specifically addresses hail damage. Colorado DORA complaint history at dora.colorado.gov affects contractor warranty integrity. Denver Class D Supervisor License must be active at warranty claim time. Installer workmanship warranties from Denver contractors typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Denver lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Capitol Hill, Country Club, and Baker historic district housing plus some 1950s-1970s Denver tract construction. Most post-1978 Denver construction is lead-free. Colorado Department of Public Health and Environment (CDPHE) administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$700 on pre-1978 Denver homes.`,
  },
  "seattle-wa": {
    localRebatesPara: `Seattle rebate stacking: Seattle City Light's Energy Smart Program combines with Puget Sound Energy's Home Weatherization Rebate to return $40-$90 per qualified Northern-zone window. Seattle's marine climate creates a specific cooling edge case: west-facing rooms in homes from Queen Anne to West Seattle experience 3-5 weeks of 80-90F afternoons in July-August. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying Northern-zone windows. Stack Seattle City Light plus PSE plus federal for meaningful combined savings. Washington has no state income tax deduction for home-improvement work.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Seattle has no hurricane exposure but Cascadia subduction zone earthquake preparation drives interest in laminated inner panes for glazing retention during shaking. Washington State Department of Natural Resources seismic hazard maps rate Capitol Hill, Magnolia, and West Seattle as moderate-to-high shaking intensity in a M8.0+ event. Laminated outer panes also address Seattle's unique sound-attenuation need: waterfront, downtown-adjacent, and airport-flight-path properties see 30-40% noise reduction with laminated glazing. Pacific winter windstorms drive 50-70 mph sustained gusts and occasional 80-100 mph bomb-cyclone events.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Seattle has 8 designated historic districts and 450+ individually landmarked properties under Seattle Landmarks Preservation Board jurisdiction including Pike Place Market, Pioneer Square, Harvard-Belmont, Ballard Avenue, Columbia City, Fort Lawton Landmark District, International District, and Sand Point Naval Air Station. Landmarked replacements require wood or wood-clad with true divided lites on contributing facades. Individually landmarked homes appear across Queen Anne, Capitol Hill, Madrona, Mount Baker, and Washington Park. Craftsman and Tudor sash profiles typically require specific 1910s-1940s restoration. Seattle Energy Code amendments require continuous exterior insulation on major renovations.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Seattle condensation management addresses marine cool climate with persistent moisture exposure. Interior condensation on window glass during winter heating is common on single-pane; dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. Seattle's sustained rain-season moisture stresses window-to-wall flashing integrity; failed flashing drives concealed wall-cavity moisture damage. HVAC humidity management and mechanical ventilation are essential in tightly-sealed modern construction. Triple-pane provides marginal benefit over dual-pane in mild Seattle winters; dual-pane argon is typically adequate. Interior moisture from cooking and bathing requires exhaust ventilation.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Seattle frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable and moisture-resistant), vinyl (Milgard is Pacific Northwest-headquartered), aluminum-clad wood (Landmark-approved), and cedar-framed wood on specific craftsman and Tudor restorations. Pure aluminum is rare in Seattle residential due to thermal bridging in marine cool climate. Dark frame colors perform adequately in Seattle's minimal UV exposure. Cedar-framed windows require specific cedar-compatible stain or semi-transparent finish every 5-7 years. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 15-18 years in Seattle's mild UV. Frame material choice matters less for UV here than in Phoenix or Vegas.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Seattle window warranty transferability: Milgard (Pacific Northwest manufacturer) offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass, transferable under specific conditions, and is the dominant Seattle brand. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Seattle's marine moisture is hard on wood frames; Milgard's fiberglass products are particularly well-suited. Washington L&I registration must be active at warranty claim time; lapsed-registration contractors forfeit homeowner surety recovery rights. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Seattle lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes the vast majority of Seattle craftsman and Tudor housing stock concentrated in Capitol Hill, Queen Anne, Ballard, Wallingford, and Madrona. Most post-WWII Seattle construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Washington Department of Ecology administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$800.`,
  },
  "austin-tx": {
    localRebatesPara: `Austin rebate stacking: Austin Energy Rebates for ENERGY STAR windows pay up to $0.75 per square foot of glass area on qualifying replacements. Austin Energy Multifamily Home Performance with ENERGY STAR adds parallel credits. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Texas has no state income tax deduction. Texas annual Q3 sales tax holiday exempts qualifying ENERGY STAR products from 6.25% state sales tax. Stack Austin Energy plus federal plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings. Austin Energy's variable-rate plans penalize summer afternoon peak usage (4-8 PM), making west-elevation SHGC upgrades ROI-positive.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Austin is outside TWIA coastal zone but Uri 2021 event prompted most Texas insurers to offer laminated glass premium credits on Austin policies. Impact-rated glazing is not required by Austin building code but is insurance-incentivized with 4-8% premium reductions common on policies renewing after 2022. Austin's south-facing Hill Country slopes in Circle C and Southwest Hills see aggressive UV exposure. Post-Uri freeze-crack resistance on windows is post-2021 spec-selection factor. Austin sits in Hill Country storm corridor with 2-4 annual damaging hail events typically. ASCE 7-22 rates Austin at 105 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Austin has 8 locally designated historic districts and 20+ National Register-listed districts under Historic Landmark Commission (HLC) jurisdiction including Hyde Park, Travis Heights, Clarksville, Old West Austin, Rainey Street Historic District, Judges Hill, Robertson Hill, West Line, East Austin MLK, Willow-Spence, Palm Memorial School, North Austin, Swedish Hill, Smoot-Terrace Park, East Avenue, Harris Ridge, and Swede Hill. Historic review requires wood or aluminum-clad wood matching original sash profiles on primary elevations. Bungalow-era homes in Hyde Park and Travis Heights often require specific 1920s-1940s sash profile matching.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Austin condensation management addresses mild winter interior condensation and summer air-conditioning condensation in Hill Country humidity. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce edge-of-glass condensation vs single-pane. Winter Storm Uri 2021 demonstrated rare cold-weather condensation vulnerability; post-Uri Austin spec increasingly includes freeze-crack-resistant product selection. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning ensures adequate dehumidification during summer humidity peaks. Triple-pane rarely pencils out in Austin due to moderate heating loads. Interior humidity from showering and cooking requires exhaust ventilation.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Austin frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized), fiberglass (thermally stable), and aluminum-clad wood (HLC-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1980s-2000s tract construction but failed widely during Uri 2021 thermal shock. Dark frame colors fade in Austin UV within 10-15 years on south and west elevations. Post-Uri freeze-crack resistance favors thicker vinyl (.046" or heavier) or fiberglass. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 12-15 years. West Austin limestone-faced homes often require specific frame-to-stone detailing.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Austin window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Austin's post-Uri freeze-crack replacement under manufacturer warranty required specific documentation; verify freeze-damage coverage on product spec before signing. City of Austin Registered Residential Building Contractor status must be active at warranty claim time. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years. Austin's rapid-growth contractor market increases warranty-enforcement complexity due to business turnover.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Austin lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Hyde Park, Travis Heights, Clarksville, and Old West Austin bungalow housing. Most post-WWII Austin construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Texas Department of State Health Services administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 Austin homes.`,
  },
  "san-francisco-ca": {
    localRebatesPara: `SF rebate stacking: PG&E's Home Efficiency Rebate Plus program plus BayREN Home+ incentives can stack to $2,000-$3,500 in combined rebates on whole-home weatherization including windows. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying windows. California CALGreen compliance may also trigger modest incentives on qualifying retrofits. Stack PG&E plus BayREN plus federal 25C for meaningful combined savings. SF's fog-belt microclimate means west-of-Twin-Peaks homes see different solar-gain economics than eastern neighborhoods.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `SF has no hurricane zone and minimal hail exposure; storm-related impact rules are about seismic retrofits rather than wind-uplift. Soft-story retrofits required by SF ordinance §34B affect window openings on ground-floor garage levels; any replacement in those openings must coordinate with structural engineer review. Laminated outer panes also provide meaningful seismic benefit: during the 1989 Loma Prieta earthquake, glazing failure was a significant injury source. Modern laminated outer panes retain shattered glass in the frame during shaking. SF Title 24 2022 requires U-0.30 maximum and SHGC 0.40 on coastal zone residential replacements.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `SF has 270+ designated landmarks under Article 10 plus 11 historic districts under Article 11 of Planning Code. Districts include Alamo Square, Jackson Square, Liberty-Hill, Dogpatch, Chinatown, Webster Street, Willis Polk Residences, Bush Street-Cottage Row, Northeast Waterfront, and South End. Landmarked replacements require wood true-divided-lite windows matching original profiles on visible elevations. Victorian and Edwardian window profiles with wavy-glass reproduction are common specifications. SF lead-safe renovation rules (pre-1978 homes) plus dust control ordinance §3428 require EPA RRP certification and HEPA-vacuum cleanup verification.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `SF condensation management addresses marine-coastal mild climate with fog-belt moisture variable by microclimate. Interior condensation on single-pane during winter heating is common; dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. Sunset and Richmond fog-belt homes see sustained moisture exposure; Mission, Bernal, Potrero sun-belt homes see minimal. HVAC humidity management through mechanical ventilation is essential in tightly-sealed SF townhouses. Triple-pane provides marginal benefit over dual-pane in mild SF climate. Interior moisture from cooking and bathing requires exhaust ventilation.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `SF frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable and moisture-resistant), vinyl (Milgard Pacific Northwest brand is well-distributed), aluminum-clad wood (Landmark-approved for historic districts), and restoration-grade wood on Victorian painted ladies. Seismic considerations affect rigid vs flexible frame selection; rigid-material fiber cement performs worse in earthquakes than flexible wood lap. Dark frame colors perform adequately in SF's minimal UV. Restoration-grade redwood and cedar on Victorian restoration require specific maintenance cadence. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 15-18 years in SF's mild UV.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `SF window warranty transferability: Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass, transferable under specific conditions. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. SF's dust-control ordinance §3428 and EPA RRP compliance on pre-1978 homes affect contractor warranty integrity. California CSLB license must be active at warranty claim time for California Homeowners Recovery Fund eligibility. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years. Victorian restoration specialty contractors may offer longer preservation-grade warranties.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `SF lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes (vast majority of SF Victorian, Edwardian, and pre-WWII housing stock). California CDPH lead-safe certification adds state-level requirement; SF dust-control ordinance §3428 imposes HEPA-vacuum cleanup verification. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. SF Department of Public Health lead-hazard disclosure applies to rental properties. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $350-$900.`,
  },
  "las-vegas-nv": {
    localRebatesPara: `Vegas rebate stacking: NV Energy's PowerShift Windows Rebate pays roughly $50 per qualified ENERGY STAR Southern-zone window, and SouthWest Gas offers stacking credits for combined envelope upgrades. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying products. Nevada has no state income tax deduction for home-improvement work. Stack NV Energy plus SouthWest Gas plus federal for meaningful combined savings. NV Energy's TOU-D residential rate plan penalizes summer afternoon peak usage (1-7 PM), making west-elevation SHGC upgrades ROI-positive on variable-rate plans.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Vegas has no hurricane exposure and monsoon season (July-September) is the primary severe-weather concern. Dust-storm debris and microbursts drive laminated outer pane demand, and many Vegas insurers offer 3-6% premium reductions on laminated glass. UV degradation is the dominant Vegas durability factor: unprotected vinyl frames on south and west elevations show measurable color fading by year 6-8 and seal failures by year 12-15. White vinyl with UV-stabilized formulation plus Low-E 366 spectrally-selective coating is the Vegas durable specification. Class 4 impact-rated glass offers modest benefit given low Vegas hail frequency.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Vegas has limited historic designation. John S. Park Historic District (1930s-1950s residential) and Huntridge Historic District (1940s-1960s) are the primary protected areas under City of Las Vegas Historic Preservation Commission. Landmarked replacements require wood or aluminum-clad wood matching original profiles. Boulder City maintains its own historic district with stricter design review. Most Vegas residential outside these districts has no historic restrictions. West Las Vegas has National Register listings but minimal local-level design review. Historic review cycles typically run 4-6 weeks on contributing structures.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Vegas condensation management is less critical than cold-climate or humid-climate metros due to dry desert conditions. Winter condensation events are rare; summer interior condensation on window glass is minimal due to low ambient humidity. Monsoon-season humidity spikes (July-September) can briefly produce interior condensation but brief durations limit damage potential. Warm-edge spacer systems provide marginal benefit in Vegas climate. HVAC humidity management is about dehumidification during monsoon humidity spikes rather than winter condensation. Triple-pane does not pencil out in Vegas; dual-pane argon is adequate.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Vegas frame material selection favors vinyl (white or light gray, UV-stabilized for extreme Vegas UV), fiberglass (thermally stable in extreme heat), and aluminum-clad wood (landmark-approved on protected districts). Pure aluminum is common on Vegas 1990s-2010s master-planned community construction; thermally-broken aluminum is the thermal-performance-acceptable variant. Dark bronze and black frame colors reach 160F+ surface temperatures in July on west-facing elevations, accelerating seal failure. UV-stabilized white or light-gray frames are Vegas-preferred. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 10-13 years in Vegas UV.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Vegas window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Vegas UV is hard on IGU seals and frame finishes; warranties typically exclude UV-related color fading on dark frames. Verify UV-specific warranty coverage on south and west elevations during spec selection. Nevada State Contractors Board C-8 glazing license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years. NRS §624.6245 deposit cap affects warranty-and-installation timing.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Vegas lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes. Most Vegas housing is post-1980 and lead-free due to the city's rapid post-1970s growth. John S. Park and Huntridge historic districts contain pre-1978 housing where EPA RRP applies. Nevada Department of Environmental Protection administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 Vegas homes (limited pool).`,
  },
  "philadelphia-pa": {
    localRebatesPara: `Philadelphia rebate stacking: PECO's Smart House Call program plus PGW conservation rebates return roughly $40-$80 per qualified Northern-zone window. Pennsylvania Housing Finance Agency (PHFA) offers low-interest financing for qualified whole-home retrofits. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying Northern-zone windows. Philadelphia's rowhouse geometry creates a specific energy advantage: shared walls with adjacent units mean only front and back elevations are exposed, concentrating window-performance payback. Stack PECO plus PGW plus federal plus PHFA for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Philadelphia has no coastal hurricane requirement for most of the metro but Delaware River flood zones in Old City, Port Richmond, and Pennsport benefit from laminated glass for impact and flood-debris resistance. The bigger Philadelphia storm concern is nor'easter wind-driven rain and snow; AL-rated 0.1 cfm per square foot or lower and reinforced meeting rails minimize air infiltration that drives most winter discomfort complaints. Philadelphia Property Maintenance Code §PM-304.13 requires operable windows in every habitable room; single-hung fixed-top replacements can fail inspection if not egress-compliant on bedroom levels. ASCE 7-22 rates Philadelphia at 100 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Philadelphia has 18,000+ historic structures and 20+ designated historic districts under Philadelphia Historical Commission jurisdiction including Society Hill, Old City, Rittenhouse, Chestnut Hill, Germantown, Powelton Village, Queen Village, Fairmount Park Historic District, and Girard Estate. Landmarked facade replacements require wood true-divided-lite windows matching original sash profiles, muntin widths, and meeting rail depths. Row house 2-over-2 and 6-over-6 sash patterns typically require specific 1880-1920 profile matching. Both L&I Contractor License AND PA HICPA registration are required on contract for any landmarked work.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Philadelphia condensation management addresses moderate cold-climate conditions with heavy summer humidity. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 15F ambient drops below 38F, causing interior condensation that damages drywall and window trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation; triple-pane provides marginal additional benefit on exposed rowhouse front-and-back elevations. HVAC humidity management through mechanical ventilation is essential. Rowhouse party-wall geometry naturally eliminates heat loss on shared elevations, concentrating condensation-prevention priority on front and back windows.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Philadelphia frame material selection favors vinyl (.046"+ gauge for cold-climate dimensional stability), fiberglass (thermally stable), aluminum-clad wood (Historical Commission-approved on landmark districts), and restoration-grade wood on landmarked Society Hill, Old City, and Chestnut Hill. Pure aluminum is rare in Philly residential due to thermal bridging. Dark frame colors absorb solar heat and show weathering in Philly freeze-thaw; lighter colors preferred on exposed elevations. Restoration-grade wood on landmarked facades requires specific 1880-1920 profile matching. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Philadelphia window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Philly freeze-thaw cycling is hard on lower-tier vinyl. Both L&I Contractor License AND PA HICPA registration must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Many Philly operators hold one but not the other, and that arrangement voids homeowner recovery rights. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years. Historical Commission-approved restoration contractors may offer specific preservation warranties.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Philadelphia lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Philly rowhouse, twin, and pre-war single-family housing stock). Pennsylvania Act 10 of 1997 and subsequent amendments govern lead hazard responsibilities; Philadelphia Lead Disclosure and Certification Law applies to rental properties. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $350-$900 on Philly rowhouses.`,
  },
  "miami-fl": {
    localRebatesPara: `Miami rebate stacking: FPL's Home Energy Survey rebates plus Florida PACE financing for full-home impact window upgrades return meaningful credit on qualifying whole-home replacements. Florida annual sales tax holiday in Q3 (typically July) exempts impact-rated windows from 7% state sales tax ($700-$2,000 savings on typical whole-home Miami replacement). Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Florida Renewable Energy Production Tax Credit adds residential solar coordination. Stack FPL plus Florida PACE plus federal plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Miami-Dade HVHZ compliance is not optional. Impact-rated glazing per TAS 201 (large missile impact test), TAS 202 (structural performance test), and TAS 203 (cyclic wind pressure test) is mandatory on every replacement window in Miami-Dade and Broward counties. The Notice of Acceptance (NOA) is the proof document. A Miami bid without specific NOA numbers is either uninformed or cutting a corner that will fail at inspection. Impact-rated windows in Miami typically add $400-$800 per opening above non-impact pricing. ASCE 7-22 rates Miami-Dade HVHZ at 175 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Miami-Dade has designated historic districts and landmarks including Coral Gables (Merrick-era Mediterranean Revival), Miami Beach Art Deco District (world's largest concentration of Art Deco architecture), MiMo Biscayne Boulevard (Miami Modernism), Morningside, South Pointe, Pinecrest-Kenwood, Stiltsville, and Virginia Key Beach. Coral Gables historic preservation authority is among the strictest in US, requiring material and profile matching to Merrick-era originals. Miami Beach Art Deco District requires specific 1920s-1940s window detailing. Approved replacements must be impact-rated AND historically appropriate, which narrows the qualified product pool significantly.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Miami condensation management addresses tropical humidity with summer air-conditioning condensation as the primary concern. Interior condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass during 85%+ humidity days can drip onto sills and damage surrounding trim. Impact-rated dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification is essential; oversized AC cycles quickly without removing humidity. Winter condensation is nearly absent in Miami's tropical climate. Hurricane-season moisture events test envelope integrity.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Miami frame material selection favors aluminum-clad wood (historically-approved for Coral Gables and Miami Beach), impact-rated fiberglass, and heavy-duty impact-rated vinyl (.060"+ gauge for HVHZ compliance). Pure aluminum impact-rated frames are common on Miami tract construction. Dark frame colors fade in Miami tropical UV within 8-12 years; light colors preferred on south and west elevations. Salt-air exposure on coastal-adjacent properties (Miami Beach, Key Biscayne, Bal Harbour) accelerates aluminum corrosion; marine-coated aluminum or non-aluminum frames are coastal-durable.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Miami window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series (Coastal Edition) offers 20-year glass non-prorated with specific coastal coverage. Pella Lifestyle Impact Resistant offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate Impact transferable warranty runs 20 years. PGT Industries (Florida-based impact specialist) offers Lifetime Warranty on qualifying products. All Miami-Dade NOA products have specific warranty tied to NOA status; NOA expires every 5-7 years and manufacturer must re-test. Florida DBPR license must be active at warranty claim time. Florida Statute §627.7152 AOB rescission window affects warranty-and-insurance coordination.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Miami lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes. Most Miami housing is post-1960 (rapid growth after 1960 plus widespread post-Andrew 1992 reconstruction) and largely post-1978. Coral Gables, Miami Beach Art Deco District, and some MiMo housing contain pre-1978 structures where EPA RRP applies. Florida Department of Health administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 Miami homes.`,
  },
  "boston-ma": {
    localRebatesPara: `Boston rebate stacking: Mass Save sponsored by Eversource and National Grid offers up to $1,500 per qualified ENERGY STAR Northern-zone window as part of whole-home weatherization packages (one of the most generous rebate programs in the country). Massachusetts Stretch Code (adopted by Boston and most surrounding municipalities) requires U-0.28 or lower in replacement scenarios plus air leakage verification at or below 0.3 cfm per square foot. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Stack Mass Save plus Stretch Code compliance plus federal for meaningful combined savings. Boston triple-deckers with 15-25 openings can capture $15,000-$30,000 in combined Mass Save plus 25C.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Boston is not a hurricane zone but nor'easter wind-driven rain and snow require high air-infiltration performance. AL-rated 0.1 cfm per square foot or lower plus reinforced meeting rails and multi-chamber frames are the Boston specification for minimizing winter interior condensation and cold-air infiltration. Triple-pane IGUs with krypton fill also address a Boston-specific comfort factor: interior surface temperature on a single-pane window at 0F ambient drops below 40F, driving condensation damage to adjacent drywall and trim. Triple-pane raises that surface temperature above 55F and eliminates the condensation problem. ASCE 7-22 rates Boston at 110 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Boston has 7 locally designated historic districts and 50+ National Register-listed districts under Boston Landmarks Commission jurisdiction. Boston Landmarks districts include Back Bay, Beacon Hill, Fort Point, South End, Bay Village, Mission Hill Triangle, and St. Botolph. Landmarked replacements require wood true-divided-lite windows with historically appropriate muntin width on primary facades. Back Bay additionally has Purple Glass requirements on specific addresses where original glass manganese chemistry turned the panes purple over time; replacements must match that coloration. Bay windows on Beacon Hill brick townhouses require specialty restoration.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Boston condensation management is critical due to sustained cold winter temperatures. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 0F ambient drops below 40F, causing interior condensation and frost that damages drywall and window trim. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.17 raise interior surface above 55F and eliminate condensation. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation further. Ice-dam water intrusion at roof-wall transitions drives additional moisture concerns; proper attic insulation (R-49 minimum) and ventilation address this at source. Interior humidity management essential during winter.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Boston frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable), .046"+ gauge vinyl (cold-climate dimensional stability), aluminum-clad wood (Boston Landmarks-approved on historic districts), and wood on Back Bay and Beacon Hill restoration. Pure aluminum is rare in Boston residential due to thermal bridging in severe cold. Back Bay Purple Glass requirement on specific addresses narrows product pool to few specialty producers. Cedar and pine on triple-decker restoration require specific priming and finishing. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years. Reinforced meeting rails and multi-chamber profiles are Boston-essential.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Boston window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Harvey Windows (New England specialty manufacturer) offers strong warranty on vinyl and fiberglass. Both MA HIC registration AND Construction Supervisor License (CSL) must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims on structural work. Mass Save rebate eligibility also requires verified licensing. Installer workmanship warranties from Boston contractors typically run 5-15 years. Boston Landmarks approval for Back Bay adds 6-10 weeks on permit timelines.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Boston lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Boston triple-decker, colonial, and pre-war housing stock). Massachusetts MA Deleading regulations are stricter than federal EPA RRP and require MA-licensed Deleader for child-occupied housing under 6 years old. Massachusetts Department of Public Health Childhood Lead Poisoning Prevention Program administers state-level requirements. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing typically runs $350-$900.`,
  },
  "san-diego-ca": {
    localRebatesPara: `San Diego rebate stacking: SDG&E's Home Energy Efficiency Rebate plus San Diego Regional Climate Action Plan incentives return $40-$75 per qualified ENERGY STAR window. California Title 24 Part 11 CALGreen requires water-resistant flashing systems documented on every replacement. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. California Mills Act property-tax reduction applies to qualifying historic landmark properties. Stack SDG&E plus San Diego Regional plus federal for meaningful combined savings. Coastal salt exposure also makes frame material selection more critical than in interior marine climates.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `San Diego has no hurricane zone but Santa Ana wind events and coastal marine humidity drive specific material selection. Fiberglass and vinyl outperform aluminum in coastal corrosion environments; any San Diego property within one mile of the coast should specify non-aluminum frames or specialty marine-coated aluminum. California WUI zones in Rancho Bernardo, Rancho Peñasquitos, and portions of East County also trigger Chapter 7A ember-resistance requirements that mandate tempered dual-pane glazing and specific vent protections. California Coastal Commission jurisdiction adds regulatory overlay for coastal-zone properties. ASCE 7-22 rates San Diego at 85 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `San Diego has multiple designated historic districts and Mills Act properties under San Diego Historic Resources Board jurisdiction including Mission Hills, Burlingame, South Park, Uptown, La Jolla, Coronado Crown-Manor, Balboa Park, Old Town San Diego State Historic Park, Gaslamp Quarter, Marston Hills, Mission Beach, Pacific Beach, Point Loma, Sherman Heights, University Heights, and West Bankers Hill. Mills Act properties (reduced property tax for historic preservation) require wood or fiberglass simulated-divided-lite windows matching original profiles. Craftsman and Spanish Colonial sash profiles typically require specific 1900s-1940s restoration.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `San Diego condensation management addresses marine-coastal climate with minimal heating and moderate cooling. Interior condensation on window glass is rare due to mild temperatures year-round. Coastal marine humidity can produce occasional interior condensation on north-facing window glass during heavily foggy mornings. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems provide adequate thermal performance for SD climate. HVAC humidity management is generally less critical than humid-climate metros. Triple-pane does not pencil out in SD; dual-pane argon is adequate.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `San Diego frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable and moisture-resistant), vinyl (Milgard Pacific Northwest brand is well-distributed), and aluminum-clad wood (Mills Act-approved for historic restoration). Pure aluminum is common on SD commercial-adjacent residential but corrodes within 5-8 years on coastal properties; marine-coated aluminum extends service. Dark frame colors perform adequately in SD's moderate UV. Mills Act historic restoration often specifies specific profile wood. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years. Stainless steel 316 hardware on coastal-adjacent properties.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `San Diego window warranty transferability: Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass, transferable under specific conditions. Andersen 400 Series (Coastal Edition for marine zones) offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. California CSLB license must be active at warranty claim time for California Homeowners Recovery Fund eligibility. SD coastal salt exposure requires specific warranty verification on non-aluminum or marine-coated products. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `San Diego lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Mission Hills, Burlingame, South Park, and some La Jolla and Point Loma craftsman housing. Most post-WWII SD construction is post-1978 and lead-free. California CDPH lead-safe certification adds state-level requirement. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$800 on pre-1978 SD homes.`,
  },
  "tampa-fl": {
    localRebatesPara: `Tampa rebate stacking: TECO Peoples Gas and Duke Energy Florida both offer Home Energy Improvement Program rebates on qualified ENERGY STAR windows. Florida annual impact-window sales tax holiday (typically July) exempts qualified products from 7% state sales tax. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Florida Renewable Energy Production Tax Credit adds residential solar coordination. Stack TECO plus Duke Energy plus federal plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings. Duke Energy TOU rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades (2-7 PM peak).`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Hillsborough and Pinellas Counties require Florida Product Approval (FPA) for wind-borne debris regions. Impact-rated glazing per FBC 1609.2 is mandatory on all replacements within one mile of the coast and is strongly recommended metro-wide for insurance-premium purposes. Citizens Property Insurance and most private Tampa carriers require impact-rated glazing or approved shutters on any policy written after 2023 for homes in designated wind-borne debris regions. Impact-rated windows add $400-$800 per opening above non-impact but are generally insurance-credit-positive within 5-8 years of installation. ASCE 7-22 rates Tampa at 140 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Tampa has 6 locally designated historic districts and multiple National Register-listed districts under Historic Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Hyde Park, Seminole Heights, Tampa Heights, Ybor City, V.M. Ybor Historic District, Tampa Bay Hotel, Old Hyde Park Preservation District, West Tampa, and Dundee Historic District. Landmark review applies to contributing structures. Impact-rated wood or aluminum-clad wood meeting historic profiles is the standard approved material on contributing facades. Florida vernacular 2-over-2 and 6-over-6 sash patterns on bungalow-era homes typically require specific 1900s-1940s profile matching. Ybor City specific cigar-factory windows require specialty restoration.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Tampa condensation management addresses tropical humidity with summer air-conditioning condensation as primary concern. Interior condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass during 85%+ humidity days can drip onto sills. Impact-rated dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification is essential; oversized AC cycles quickly without removing humidity. Winter condensation is rare in Tampa's hot-humid climate. Hurricane-season moisture events test envelope integrity.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Tampa frame material selection favors impact-rated vinyl (.060"+ gauge for FPA compliance), impact-rated fiberglass (thermally stable and humidity-resistant), aluminum-clad wood (Historic Preservation-approved for landmark districts), and heavy-duty impact-rated aluminum. Dark frame colors fade in Tampa tropical UV within 8-12 years. Salt-air exposure on coastal-adjacent properties (Clearwater Beach, St. Pete Beach, Treasure Island) accelerates aluminum corrosion. Marine-coated aluminum or non-aluminum frames are coastal-durable. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Tampa window warranty transferability: PGT Industries (Florida-based impact specialist) offers Lifetime Warranty on qualifying products and is well-suited to Gulf Coast. Andersen 400 Series (Coastal Edition) offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle Impact Resistant offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate Impact transferable warranty runs 20 years. All FPA-approved products have specific warranty tied to product-approval status. Florida DBPR license must be active at warranty claim time. Florida Statute §627.7152 AOB rescission window affects warranty-and-insurance coordination on hurricane-related claims.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Tampa lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes. Most Tampa housing is post-1950 (rapid growth after 1950s) with mix of pre-1978 and post-1978 construction. Tampa historic districts (Hyde Park, Seminole Heights, Tampa Heights, Ybor City) contain pre-1978 housing where EPA RRP applies. Florida Department of Health administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },
  "detroit-mi": {
    localRebatesPara: `Detroit rebate stacking: DTE Energy's Home Energy Consultation plus Consumers Energy efficiency rebates return $40-$90 per qualified Northern-zone window. Michigan's 2015-amended Energy Code requires air-leakage verification on whole-home weatherization jobs receiving DTE or Consumers Energy rebate funding; blower-door test is typically done before and after the retrofit. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Michigan state income tax deduction applies to qualifying home-improvement work. Stack DTE plus Consumers Energy plus federal plus state deduction for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Detroit is not a hurricane zone but Great Lakes winter winds drive high air-infiltration requirements. AL 0.1 cfm per square foot or lower and reinforced meeting rails are Detroit specification for minimizing cold-air infiltration. Laminated outer panes also address Detroit-specific factor: neighborhood security concerns in transitioning areas make laminated inner panes practical upgrade that qualifies for insurance premium reduction in several zip codes. The 2023 derecho event produced widespread wind damage across Oakland and Macomb counties. ASCE 7-22 rates Detroit at 105 mph design wind speed. DTE conservation improvement rebates also stack with federal 25C tax credit through 2032.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Detroit has 20+ designated historic districts under Detroit Historic Designation Advisory Board jurisdiction including Boston-Edison, Indian Village, Woodbridge, Palmer Park, Corktown, East Ferry Avenue, Atkinson Avenue, Willis-Selden, West Canfield, Brush Park, Virginia Park, Prentis Avenue, Arden Park-East Boston, Hubbard Farms, Warren Avenue West, Parkview, New Center Commercial, Cass-Davenport, Piquette Avenue, and Thirteen-Hundred Block East Lafayette. Landmarked replacements require wood windows with historically appropriate profiles on primary and often secondary facades. Bungalow 6-over-1 and Arts-and-Crafts 4-over-1 sash typically require specific 1910s-1940s profile matching.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Detroit condensation management is critical due to sustained cold winter temperatures and Great Lakes lake-effect moisture. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at -5F ambient drops below 35F, causing interior condensation and frost. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.18 raise interior surface above 55F and eliminate condensation. Warm-edge spacer systems reduce edge-of-glass condensation. Ice-dam water intrusion at roof-wall transitions drives additional moisture concerns; proper attic insulation (R-49 minimum) and ventilation address this at source. Interior humidity management during winter essential.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Detroit frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable), .046"+ gauge vinyl (cold-climate dimensional stability), aluminum-clad wood (Detroit HDAB-approved on historic districts), and restoration-grade wood on Boston-Edison and Indian Village landmarks. Pure aluminum is rare in Detroit residential due to thermal bridging. Detroit's freeze-thaw cycling is particularly hard on lower-tier vinyl; thin-gauge products often fail before warranty expiration. Dark frame colors show weathering in Detroit freeze-thaw; lighter colors preferred on exposed elevations. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Detroit window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Detroit's severe freeze-thaw is hard on lower-tier products; verify warranty coverage specifically addresses Detroit-climate thermal cycling. Michigan LARA Residential Builder license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Michigan MCL §339.2411 three-day right-of-rescission applies to any in-home sale. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Detroit lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes (vast majority of Detroit housing stock, particularly 1910s-1940s brick bungalow and Arts-and-Crafts homes). Michigan Department of Health and Human Services Lead Safe Home Program administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Michigan also has specific lead-abatement licensing requirements on residential property. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$700.`,
  },
  "minneapolis-mn": {
    localRebatesPara: `Minneapolis rebate stacking: Xcel Energy Minnesota plus CenterPoint Energy rebates return $75-$150 per qualified Northern-zone window under the Home Energy Squad conservation program. Minnesota Energy Code mandates air leakage of 0.3 cfm per square foot maximum and blower-door test on any home receiving conservation improvement funds. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Stack Xcel plus CenterPoint plus federal plus Home Energy Squad for meaningful combined savings. Minnesota's severe cold climate makes triple-pane upgrades particularly valuable for heating-bill reduction.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Minneapolis is not a hurricane zone but sustained -20F winter temperatures make triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs the practical spec. The Minneapolis-specific comfort factor is interior frame surface temperature: vinyl frames with only one or two hollow chambers conduct enough cold at -20F ambient to create frost on interior surfaces and damage adjacent drywall. Fiberglass frames and multi-chamber fibrex composites perform measurably better. Minneapolis also sees 2-4 annual damaging hail events; Class 4 impact-rated glass qualifies for insurance premium reductions. ASCE 7-22 rates Minneapolis at 105 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Minneapolis has 10+ locally designated historic districts and multiple National Register-listed districts under Minneapolis Heritage Preservation Commission jurisdiction including Milwaukee Avenue, Nicollet Island, Healy Block, Fourth Avenue Historic District, Stevens Square, Fulton Neighborhood, Washburn-Fair Oaks Mansion, Saint Anthony Falls, Warehouse Historic District, and Grain Belt Brewery Complex. Landmarked replacements require wood windows with matching sash profiles and divided lites on historic facades. Bungalow 6-over-1 and four-square 4-over-1 sash typically require specific 1920s-1950s profile matching on primary facades.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Minneapolis condensation management is the most critical of any major US metro due to sustained -20F winter extremes. Double-pane glass at -20F ambient drops interior surface temperature below 32F, causing interior condensation and frost. Triple-pane krypton-filled IGUs reaching U-0.17 eliminate that failure mode and raise interior surface above 55F. Warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) reduce edge-of-glass condensation further. Fiberglass and fibrex composite frames outperform pure vinyl on cold-ambient interior surface temperature because expansion rates match glass, keeping seals tighter longer.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Minneapolis frame material selection strongly favors fiberglass and fibrex composite for interior-surface-temperature performance at -20F ambient. Vinyl (.046"+ gauge, multi-chamber) is acceptable but less optimal. Aluminum-clad wood (Heritage Preservation Commission-approved on historic districts) provides good thermal performance but is higher cost. Pure aluminum is prohibited for Minneapolis residential due to severe thermal bridging; thermally-broken aluminum is marginally acceptable. Dark frame colors perform adequately in Minneapolis's moderate UV exposure. Marvin and Andersen both have Minnesota-based roots and strong regional presence.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Minneapolis window warranty transferability: Marvin (headquartered in Warroad MN) offers Ultimate transferable warranty 20 years on original and subsequent owners, strong Minnesota-made product. Andersen (headquartered in Bayport MN) 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, strong Minnesota-made product. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Minnesota LARA Residential Building Contractor license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Minnesota's severe freeze-thaw is hard on lower-tier products; verify warranty specifically addresses Minnesota-climate thermal cycling and -20F operating conditions.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Minneapolis lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes 1920s-1950s bungalow and four-square housing concentrated in Uptown, Linden Hills, Lowry Hill, and Nokomis. Most post-WWII Twin Cities construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Minnesota Department of Health Lead Program administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$700 on pre-1978 Minneapolis homes.`,
  },
  "charlotte-nc": {
    localRebatesPara: `Charlotte rebate stacking: Duke Energy's Smart $aver Residential Program plus Charlotte Water conservation credits return $30-$70 per qualified Southern-zone window with SHGC 0.25 or lower. The Piedmont climate's heavy humidity cycling makes 20-year factory warranties on the IGU specifically more valuable than in drier climates. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Stack Duke plus Charlotte Water plus federal for meaningful combined savings. Duke Energy TOU rate plans reward peak-hour demand reduction from west-elevation SHGC upgrades.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Charlotte is not a coastal hurricane zone but Charlotte Regional Tornado Alley corridor and 2024 insurance revisions incentivize impact-rated glazing. Premium credits of 5-10% are common on Charlotte policies upgraded with laminated outer panes on west and south elevations. North Carolina has strengthened wind-uplift requirements in wake of 2018 Hurricane Florence and 2020 severe-weather outbreak, and Charlotte-area code officials increasingly enforce these requirements even though the metro sits 200 miles inland from the coast. ASCE 7-22 rates Charlotte at 110 mph design wind speed. Hail-corridor exposure favors Class 4 impact-rated glass.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Charlotte-Mecklenburg has designated historic districts under Historic District Commission jurisdiction including Dilworth, Wesley Heights, Fourth Ward, Plaza Midwood, Wilmore, Hermitage Court, Chantilly, Oaklawn Park, Biddleville-Seversville, Greenville, McCrorey Heights, and North Charlotte. Landmarked replacements require wood or aluminum-clad wood matching original sash profiles. Commission review typically runs 3-6 weeks before permit issuance. Craftsman 6-over-1 and bungalow 4-over-1 sash on Dilworth and Plaza Midwood typically require specific 1920s-1940s profile matching. North Carolina Residential Code amendments require hurricane ties on some inland construction.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Charlotte condensation management addresses Piedmont humidity cycling with moderate winter interior condensation and summer air-conditioning condensation. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 20F ambient drops below 40F, causing interior condensation. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation vs single-pane. Summer humidity-driven condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass can drip onto sills. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification is essential. Piedmont's heavy humidity cycling stresses IGU seals; factory-sealed units from major manufacturers hold up better than small-shop products.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Charlotte frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized), fiberglass (thermally stable and humidity-resistant), and aluminum-clad wood (Historic District Commission-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1970s-1990s Charlotte tract construction but thermally-broken aluminum is the thermal-performance-acceptable variant. Dark frame colors fade in Charlotte UV within 10-15 years. Humidity-driven biological growth on north-facing frames requires regular cleaning. Termite barrier at grade level essential on wood frames. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Charlotte window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Piedmont humidity cycling is hard on IGU seals; 20-year warranties deliver measurable value. North Carolina Licensing Board for General Contractors license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims on jobs over $30,000. SouthPark, Ballantyne, and Myers Park HOA approval may be required before warranty-related custom-profile orders ship. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Charlotte lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Dilworth and Plaza Midwood bungalow housing plus some 1940s-1970s Charlotte single-family. Most post-1980 Charlotte tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free. North Carolina Department of Health and Human Services Childhood Lead Poisoning Prevention Program administers state-level requirements. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Specific work practices including HEPA-vacuum cleanup, plastic sheeting containment, and clearance testing are required. Lead-paint testing typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },

  "st-louis-mo": {
    localRebatesPara: `St. Louis rebate stacking: Ameren Missouri's ActOnEnergy program pays $40-$85 per qualified ENERGY STAR window on residential retrofits across the Greater St. Louis service territory. Spire Energy (formerly Laclede Gas) adds parallel conservation credits on gas-heated homes with documented blower-door test improvement. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying ENERGY STAR products meeting IECC Zone 4A targets. Missouri Department of Natural Resources Home Energy Loan Program (HELP) offers below-market-rate financing for qualifying whole-home envelope retrofits. Stack Ameren plus Spire plus federal plus Missouri HELP for meaningful combined savings on 15-25 opening whole-house jobs typical of Soulard four-family flats.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `St. Louis sits in the western extension of Tornado Alley, and the metro has direct tornado history including the 2011 Lambert Airport EF4 event and the 2022 Maryland Heights outbreak. Impact-rated glazing is not required by City of St. Louis or St. Louis County building code but delivers meaningful insurance premium reduction (4-7%) on policies renewed after 2023 with State Farm, Shelter Insurance, and American Family carriers dominant in the Missouri market. Class 4 laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing elevations provide combined hail and tornado-debris resistance. ASCE 7-22 rates the St. Louis metro at 115 mph design wind speed with Exposure B/C for most residential parcels.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `St. Louis has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Cultural Resources Office governing 120+ locally designated landmarks plus National Register districts including Lafayette Square (Missouri's first historic district), Soulard, Benton Park, Fox Park, Tower Grove East, Tower Grove South, Shaw, Compton Heights, Central West End, Skinker-DeBaliviere, and the St. Louis Place Historic District. CRO review requires wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement with matching 1870s-1920s sash profiles, divided-lite configurations, and muntin widths on contributing facades. Lafayette Square's ornate Italianate and Second Empire window profiles with arched heads and bracketed hoods are among the most prescriptive restoration requirements in the Midwest. Vinyl categorically prohibited on contributing structures within locally designated districts.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `St. Louis condensation management addresses the Mississippi Valley's distinctive humidity pattern where winter relative humidity averages 72-78% due to river-proximity moisture. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 15F ambient drops below 38F in Central West End brick four-family flats, causing interior condensation that damages century-old plaster walls and ornamental wood trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems (Super Spacer, Edgetech, Cardinal) raise interior surface temperature above 52F and reduce condensation damage. Summer humidity-driven condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass is a secondary St. Louis concern; HVAC dehumidification through properly sized equipment is essential during the July-August humidity peak that averages 76F dew point.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `St. Louis frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable across freeze-thaw cycling), .046"+ gauge vinyl (dimensionally stable in St. Louis cold), aluminum-clad wood (CRO-approved on historic districts), and restoration-grade wood on Lafayette Square and Compton Heights landmarked Victorians. Pure aluminum is rare in St. Louis residential due to thermal bridging in the mixed-humid climate. Dark frame colors show weathering in St. Louis freeze-thaw within 8-12 years on south and west exposures. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 12-15 years. Termite barrier at grade level is important on wood frames given St. Louis's position in the Formosan termite expansion zone.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `St. Louis window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, 10-year components. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years on original and subsequent owners. Window World (headquartered in North Wilkesboro NC but with major St. Louis franchised presence) offers Lifetime Limited Warranty with specific transferability conditions. St. Louis's Mississippi Valley humidity is hard on IGU seals; factory-sealed units from major manufacturers hold up measurably better than regional unknown brands. Missouri Division of Professional Registration contractor status must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `St. Louis lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes the vast majority of St. Louis City housing stock (approximately 85% of structures predate 1960). Soulard, Lafayette Square, Benton Park, Shaw, and Tower Grove neighborhoods contain dense concentrations of pre-1900 housing with multiple layers of lead paint on window sash, trim, and glazing putty. Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services Lead Poisoning Prevention Program administers state-level lead hazard requirements. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. City of St. Louis Health Department tracks elevated blood lead levels by ward and publishes neighborhood-specific risk maps. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$750 per property.`,
  },
  "orlando-fl": {
    localRebatesPara: `Orlando rebate stacking: Duke Energy Florida's Home Energy Improvement Program returns roughly $35-$65 per qualified ENERGY STAR Southern-zone window. Orlando Utilities Commission residential customers in OUC territory qualify for separate OUC-specific rebates on qualifying products. Florida annual impact-window sales tax holiday (typically July) exempts qualified products from 6% state sales tax plus Orange County surtax. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Florida PACE financing through Ygrene or Renew Financial covers full-home impact window upgrades with property-tax-attached repayment. Stack Duke Energy plus OUC plus federal plus PACE plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Orlando sits within Orange County's wind-borne debris region under Florida Building Code 2023 §1609.2, requiring impact-rated windows or approved protective systems on all replacement openings. Florida Product Approval (FPA) documentation is verified at permit final by Orange County Building Safety Division inspectors. Impact-rated laminated glazing per ASTM E1886/E1996 large-missile test adds $350-$700 per opening above non-impact pricing but delivers 8-15% insurance premium reduction on most Orlando homeowners policies through Citizens Property Insurance and private carriers. The 2024 hurricane season's near-miss on the I-4 corridor intensified insurer enforcement of impact-glazing requirements on policy renewals across Seminole and Orange counties.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Orlando proper has limited historic designation, but Winter Park Historic Preservation Board oversees contributing structures in the Hannibal Square, Virginia Heights, College Quarter, and Park Avenue Historic Districts with strict material-and-profile-matching requirements. Winter Park landmarked replacements require wood or aluminum-clad wood with 1920s-1940s Mediterranean Revival and craftsman sash profiles on primary facades; vinyl and standard aluminum are prohibited on contributing structures. College Park Historic Preservation District in Orlando also restricts window replacement on contributing 1920s-1940s bungalows. Maitland and Eatonville each maintain separate historic preservation authority with independent review timelines running 3-6 weeks before permit issuance.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Orlando condensation management addresses subtropical humidity with summer air-conditioning condensation as the primary concern. Interior condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass during 90%+ humidity days along the Butler Chain of Lakes can drip onto sills and damage surrounding trim within a single cooling season. Impact-rated dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation risk. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification is essential; oversized AC systems in Orlando tract construction cycle too quickly and leave indoor humidity above 60% RH even while achieving temperature setpoint. Winter condensation is effectively absent in Orlando's tropical climate.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Orlando frame material selection favors impact-rated vinyl (.060"+ gauge for FPA compliance on wind-borne debris region installations), impact-rated fiberglass (thermally stable in subtropical heat), and aluminum-clad wood (Winter Park Historic Preservation Board-approved for landmark districts). Standard aluminum impact-rated frames are common on Orlando tract construction across Waterford Lakes, Avalon Park, and Lake Nona. Dark frame colors fade in Orlando subtropical UV within 7-10 years; light colors extend service life. Salt-air exposure is minimal in landlocked Orlando unlike coastal Florida metros, reducing corrosion concerns. Fluoropolymer finishes (Kynar, Fluoropon) hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Orlando window warranty transferability: PGT Industries (Florida-based impact specialist, headquartered in Venice FL) offers Lifetime Warranty on qualifying WinGuard products specifically designed for Florida wind-borne debris regions. Andersen 400 Series (Coastal Edition) offers 20-year glass non-prorated with specific coastal coverage. Pella Lifestyle Impact Resistant offers 20-year glass. All FPA-approved products have specific warranty tied to product-approval status; FPA expires every 7 years and manufacturer must re-test. Florida DBPR license must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Installer workmanship warranties from Orlando contractors typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Orlando lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes. Most Orlando housing is post-1970 due to the region's explosive growth following Walt Disney World's 1971 opening, so the pre-1978 housing pool is relatively small compared to northeastern metros. Winter Park, College Park, and downtown Orlando contain the primary concentrations of pre-1978 construction where EPA RRP applies. Florida Department of Health administers state-level lead hazard program. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed on qualifying pre-1978 structures. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$600 on pre-1978 Orlando-area homes.`,
  },
  "san-antonio-tx": {
    localRebatesPara: `San Antonio rebate stacking: CPS Energy's residential efficiency programs return $35-$70 per qualified ENERGY STAR Southern-zone window with SHGC 0.25 or lower. CPS Energy is the nation's largest municipally owned electric and gas utility, and its Casa Verde weatherization program funds complete window replacements on income-qualifying Bexar County homes. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Texas has no state income tax deduction. Texas annual Q3 sales tax holiday exempts qualifying ENERGY STAR products from 6.25% state sales tax. Stack CPS Energy plus federal plus sales tax holiday for meaningful combined savings on whole-home replacements across the Alamo City.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `San Antonio is outside the Texas Windstorm Insurance Association (TWIA) coastal zone, and impact-rated glazing is not required by City of San Antonio or Bexar County building code. However, San Antonio sits in the South-Central Texas hail corridor where 3-5 annual damaging hail events routinely damage residential windows. Class 4 impact-rated glazing delivers 5-10% insurance premium reduction on most San Antonio policies written after 2022 with USAA (headquartered at USAA Boulevard in San Antonio), State Farm, and Allstate carriers. ASCE 7-22 rates San Antonio at 105 mph design wind speed. Post-Winter Storm Uri 2021 freeze-crack replacements also benefit from laminated inner panes.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `San Antonio has one of the most extensive historic preservation programs in Texas under the Office of Historic Preservation (OHP) governing the King William Historic District (Texas's first historic district, established 1968), Monte Vista, Tobin Hill, Dignowity Hill, Government Hill, Lavaca, Mahncke Park, Alta Vista, Denver Heights, Beacon Hill, and portions of Southtown. OHP review on contributing structures requires wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement matching original 1870s-1930s sash profiles and divided-lite configurations. King William's ornate Victorian and Italianate window profiles with arched heads require specialty manufacturer orders with 10-14 week lead times. San Antonio Conservation Society advocacy ensures enforcement rigor.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `San Antonio condensation management addresses South Texas humidity with summer air-conditioning condensation as the primary concern. Interior condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass during 85%+ humidity days in the San Antonio River corridor can drip onto sills and damage trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. HVAC humidity management through properly sized air conditioning with adequate dehumidification is essential; military housing developments near Lackland, Randolph, and Fort Sam Houston frequently have oversized AC units from original construction that cycle too quickly. Winter condensation events are rare but Uri 2021-style freeze events produce brief interior condensation vulnerability.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `San Antonio frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for South Texas sun), fiberglass (thermally stable in 105F+ summer ambient), and aluminum-clad wood (OHP-approved on King William, Monte Vista, and Tobin Hill landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1970s-1990s San Antonio tract construction and conducts heat aggressively in summer; it is the dominant failure pattern across northeast-side military housing. Dark frame colors fade in San Antonio UV within 10-15 years on south and west exposures. Post-Uri freeze-crack resistance favors thicker vinyl (.046" or heavier) or fiberglass. Texas Hill Country limestone-faced homes along the Balcones Escarpment require specialty frame-to-stone flashing details.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `San Antonio window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated, 10-year components. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. USAA (headquartered in San Antonio) homeowners insurance interacts with manufacturer warranties on hail-damage claims; Class 4 impact-rated products provide smoother claims processing with USAA adjusters familiar with the product tier. Texas has no state installer license, so installer warranty enforceability centers on insurance certificates and bond status. Post-Uri freeze-crack replacement claims required specific manufacturer documentation. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `San Antonio lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes King William, Monte Vista, Dignowity Hill, Government Hill, and Lavaca historic district housing plus some pre-WWII military housing near Fort Sam Houston. Most post-1960 San Antonio tract construction is post-1978 and lead-free. Texas Department of State Health Services administers state-level lead hazard program. Bexar County Health Department tracks elevated blood lead levels and publishes neighborhood-specific risk assessments. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 San Antonio homes.`,
  },
  "portland-or": {
    localRebatesPara: `Portland rebate stacking: Energy Trust of Oregon (funded by Portland General Electric and Pacific Power ratepayers) returns $50-$100 per qualified Northern-zone window on residential retrofits. Northwest Natural Gas conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes across the Portland metro. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying ENERGY STAR products meeting IECC Zone 4C targets. Oregon has no statewide sales tax, eliminating one variable from the cost equation. Stack Energy Trust plus NW Natural plus federal for meaningful combined savings on whole-home Willamette Valley retrofits.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Portland has no hurricane exposure, and severe weather concerns center on Cascadia Subduction Zone earthquake preparedness and periodic ice storm events like the devastating February 2021 storm that downed thousands of trees across the metro. Laminated inner panes provide seismic glazing-retention benefit during earthquake shaking, relevant throughout the Portland metro where the Oregon Department of Geology and Mineral Industries rates expected shaking intensity at MMI VII-VIII in a M9.0 Cascadia event. Columbia Gorge windstorms drive 50-80 mph gusts through East Portland and Troutdale corridors. ASCE 7-22 rates Portland at 100 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Portland has extensive historic preservation coverage under Portland Historic Landmarks Commission governing designated landmarks and districts including Alphabet Historic District, Ladd's Addition, Irvington, Piedmont, King's Hill, Lair Hill, Skidmore/Old Town, and the Yamhill Historic District. Portland's designated Conservation Districts (including Eliot, Woodlawn, Buckman, and Sunnyside) impose additional design review on exterior alterations including window replacement. Landmarked replacements require wood or wood-clad windows matching original 1890s-1930s craftsman and Foursquare sash profiles. Vinyl is prohibited on contributing structures. Alberta Arts District bungalows from the 1910s-1920s often require specific divided-lite configurations. Commission review typically runs 4-8 weeks.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Portland condensation management addresses the Willamette Valley's persistent marine moisture with sustained rain-season exposure from October through May. Interior condensation on single-pane during winter heating is common in craftsman homes across Hawthorne, Division, and Belmont corridors. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems reduce condensation. Portland's persistent rain stresses window-to-wall flashing integrity; failed flashing drives concealed wall-cavity moisture damage that inspectors flag on roughly 55% of pre-1940 homes during energy audits. HVAC humidity management through mechanical ventilation (HRV or ERV) is essential in tightly sealed Portland retrofits. Triple-pane provides marginal benefit over dual-pane in Portland's mild marine winter.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Portland frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable and moisture-resistant, ideal for Portland rain exposure), vinyl (Milgard Pacific Northwest brand is dominant regional choice), aluminum-clad wood (Historic Landmarks Commission-approved), and cedar-framed wood on specific craftsman and Foursquare restorations. Pure aluminum is rare in Portland residential due to thermal bridging. Dark frame colors perform adequately in Portland's minimal UV exposure. Cedar and Douglas fir-framed windows on craftsman restorations require specific marine-grade stain or semi-transparent finish every 5-7 years due to persistent moisture exposure. Jeld-Wen (formerly headquartered in Klamath Falls OR) also has strong Pacific Northwest distribution.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Portland window warranty transferability: Milgard (Pacific Northwest manufacturer, headquartered in Tacoma WA) offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass with strong regional distribution and service. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Portland's persistent moisture is hard on wood frames and inferior weatherstripping. Oregon CCB registration must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims and surety recovery. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years. Energy Trust of Oregon rebate eligibility requires verified CCB registration.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Portland lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes the vast majority of Portland craftsman, Foursquare, and pre-WWII housing stock concentrated in inner Northeast (Irvington, Alameda, Beaumont-Wilshire), inner Southeast (Sellwood-Moreland, Hawthorne, Ladd's Addition), and Northwest (Alphabet District, Nob Hill). Oregon Health Authority Lead-Based Paint Program administers state-level requirements with specific Oregon-adopted amendments to federal EPA RRP. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$750 on pre-1978 Portland homes.`,
  },
  "sacramento-ca": {
    localRebatesPara: `Sacramento rebate stacking: SMUD's Home Performance Program offers rebates of $50-$100 per qualified ENERGY STAR window, among the most generous municipal utility programs in California. PG&E service-area homes in unincorporated Sacramento County qualify for separate PG&E Home Efficiency Rebate Plus credits. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. California Title 24 CALGreen compliance triggers additional modular incentives on qualifying retrofits. California Mills Act property-tax reduction applies to qualifying historic landmark properties. Stack SMUD plus federal plus Mills Act for meaningful combined savings on qualifying East Sacramento and Midtown retrofits.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Sacramento has no hurricane exposure, and severe weather concerns center on Central Valley summer heat extremes and occasional severe thunderstorm events. The July 2022 Electra Fire and the recurring Sacramento River Delta wind events drive modest interest in impact-resistant glazing. California WUI zones in portions of El Dorado Hills, Folsom, and Auburn-area foothills trigger Chapter 7A ember-resistance requirements that mandate tempered dual-pane glazing. Sacramento's flat Valley floor sees minimal wind-driven debris risk compared to foothill communities. ASCE 7-22 rates Sacramento at 85 mph design wind speed. Insurance premium credits for laminated glass are modest (2-4%) compared to hail-belt or hurricane-zone markets.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Sacramento has designated historic districts under the Sacramento Preservation Commission including the Washington Historic District, Alkali Flat, Boulevard Park, Newton Booth, Marshall Gold Discovery Area, Southside Park, Newton Booth, and Old Sacramento State Historic Park. East Sacramento's Fabulous 40s neighborhood contains individually landmarked homes requiring specific 1920s-1940s Tudor, Colonial Revival, and Mediterranean Revival window profiles. Midtown Sacramento grid housing includes pre-1920 Victorians requiring wood true-divided-lite restoration. Sacramento Preservation Commission review typically runs 4-6 weeks before permit issuance. Mills Act contracts require ongoing maintenance verification.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Sacramento condensation management addresses the Central Valley's tule fog season (November-February) when persistent ground-level fog keeps outdoor humidity above 90% for days at a time while indoor heating runs continuously. Interior condensation on single-pane at 32F ambient during tule fog events drops glass surface temperature to dew point and produces runoff that damages window sills and adjacent plaster on pre-war East Sacramento homes. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface temperature above condensation threshold. Summer condensation is rare due to Sacramento's dry summer climate (typical July relative humidity below 25% by afternoon).`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Sacramento frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for Central Valley sun that pushes summer surface temperatures above 140F on dark frames), fiberglass (thermally stable across Sacramento's 35F-to-110F annual temperature range), and aluminum-clad wood (Sacramento Preservation Commission-approved on landmark districts). Pure aluminum is common on 1960s-1980s Rancho Cordova and North Highlands tract construction but conducts heat aggressively in Central Valley summer. SMUD Home Performance Program requires NFRC-certified products for rebate eligibility. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 10-13 years in Sacramento's severe Valley UV exposure.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Sacramento window warranty transferability: Milgard (strong West Coast presence) offers Full Lifetime Warranty on vinyl and fiberglass, transferable under specific conditions. Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Sacramento's Central Valley UV and temperature extremes are hard on IGU seals; verify warranty coverage specifically addresses high-temperature seal performance on south and west elevations. California CSLB license must be active at warranty claim time for California Homeowners Recovery Fund eligibility. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Sacramento lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes East Sacramento, Midtown, Land Park, and Curtis Park housing dating from the 1900s-1950s. Most post-WWII Sacramento suburban construction (Elk Grove, Natomas, Rancho Cordova) is post-1978 and lead-free. California CDPH lead-safe certification adds state-level requirement beyond federal EPA RRP. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Sacramento County Environmental Management Department publishes lead-hazard information for older neighborhoods. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $300-$750 on pre-1978 Sacramento homes.`,
  },
  "pittsburgh-pa": {
    localRebatesPara: `Pittsburgh rebate stacking: Duquesne Light's Watt Choices residential program returns $40-$85 per qualified Northern-zone window on residential retrofits. Columbia Gas conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes across the Allegheny County service territory. Pennsylvania Act 129 energy-efficiency mandates fund additional utility-administered conservation incentives beyond baseline programs. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies to qualifying Northern-zone ENERGY STAR products. Pennsylvania Housing Finance Agency (PHFA) low-interest financing applies to qualifying whole-home weatherization. Stack Duquesne Light plus Columbia Gas plus federal plus PHFA for meaningful combined savings.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Pittsburgh is not a hurricane zone, but the Ohio Valley severe-storm corridor produces 2-4 annual damaging hail and wind events across Allegheny, Westmoreland, and Washington counties. The June 2022 derecho event caused widespread residential glazing damage across the South Hills and Mon Valley communities. Laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing glazing deliver 4-8% insurance premium reduction on most Pittsburgh policies with Erie Insurance (headquartered in Erie PA), Travelers, and State Farm carriers. ASCE 7-22 rates Pittsburgh at 105 mph design wind speed. Pittsburgh's river-valley topography channels storm winds through narrow corridors in Lawrenceville, Strip District, and South Side.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Pittsburgh has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Pittsburgh Historic Review Commission governing locally designated districts and landmarks including Allegheny West, Manchester, Mexican War Streets, Deutschtown (East Allegheny), Shadyside, Oakland Civic Center, Lawrenceville, South Side Flats, Mount Washington, and the Strip District. Pittsburgh History and Landmarks Foundation provides additional advocacy and design review support. Landmarked replacements require wood or aluminum-clad wood matching original 1870s-1920s sash profiles. Victorian-era Allegheny West homes with ornate bracketed hoods and arched window heads require specialty restoration manufacturers. Review typically runs 4-8 weeks.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Pittsburgh condensation management addresses the Three Rivers microclimate where river-proximity moisture raises winter relative humidity above regional averages. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 10F ambient drops below 35F in Shadyside and Squirrel Hill brick row houses, causing interior condensation that damages century-old plaster and wood trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface above 50F and reduce condensation. Triple-pane with krypton fill is the performance spec for exposed hillside homes in Mount Washington, Spring Hill, and Troy Hill where winter wind exposure from the river valleys intensifies convective heat loss beyond what sheltered valley-floor homes experience.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Pittsburgh frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable across the Allegheny Plateau's freeze-thaw cycling), .046"+ gauge vinyl (dimensionally stable in Pittsburgh cold), aluminum-clad wood (Historic Review Commission-approved on designated districts), and restoration-grade wood on Allegheny West and Manchester landmarked Victorians. Pure aluminum is rare in Pittsburgh residential due to thermal bridging. Pittsburgh's industrial-era soot legacy means older window trim and frames require thorough cleaning before replacement flashing integration. Dark frame colors show weathering in Pittsburgh freeze-thaw within 8-12 years. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Pittsburgh window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Harvey Windows (strong Northeast regional presence) offers competitive warranty on vinyl and fiberglass. Pittsburgh's freeze-thaw cycling and river-valley humidity stress IGU seals; factory-sealed units from major manufacturers outperform regional unknowns. Pennsylvania HICPA registration must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims and Attorney General recovery. Erie Insurance (headquartered in PA) interacts with manufacturer warranties on Ohio Valley hail-damage claims. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Pittsburgh lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes the vast majority of Pittsburgh housing stock across Shadyside, Squirrel Hill, Lawrenceville, Bloomfield, Polish Hill, and the North Side neighborhoods. Pittsburgh's pre-war brick housing dates overwhelmingly to the 1890s-1940s steel-era boom and contains multiple layers of lead paint on window sash, trim, and glazing putty. Pennsylvania Act 10 of 1997 governs lead hazard responsibilities. Allegheny County Health Department Lead Poisoning Prevention Program publishes neighborhood-specific risk data and tracks elevated blood lead levels by census tract. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $350-$800.`,
  },
  "columbus-oh": {
    localRebatesPara: `Columbus rebate stacking: AEP Ohio's Home Energy Solutions program returns $40-$80 per qualified Northern-zone window on residential retrofits. Columbia Gas of Ohio conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes across the Franklin County service territory. Ohio Home Weatherization Assistance Program (HWAP) covers income-qualified full replacements. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Ohio state income tax deduction applies to qualifying home-improvement work. Stack AEP Ohio plus Columbia Gas plus federal plus HWAP for meaningful combined savings on whole-home retrofits across Central Ohio.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Columbus is not a hurricane zone, but Central Ohio sits in the Ohio Valley severe-storm corridor where 2-4 annual damaging hail events and periodic tornado outbreaks affect residential glazing. The 2024 Licking County tornado outbreak damaged homes across Newark, Granville, and eastern Franklin County suburbs. Laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing glazing deliver 4-7% insurance premium reduction on most Columbus policies with Nationwide (headquartered in Columbus), State Farm, and Progressive (headquartered in Mayfield Village OH) carriers. ASCE 7-22 rates Columbus at 105 mph design wind speed with flat-terrain Exposure C for most suburban parcels.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Columbus has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Columbus Historic Resources Commission governing locally designated districts including German Village (the largest privately funded historic restoration project in the United States, 233 acres), Victorian Village, Italian Village, Olde Town East, Brewery District, Hungarian Village, Near East Side, Harrison West, and Short North Arch District. German Village Commission review is among the most prescriptive in the Midwest, requiring wood windows with specific 1840s-1900s sash profiles, divided-lite configurations, and handmade brick color-matching on surrounding masonry. Vinyl categorically prohibited on German Village contributing structures.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Columbus condensation management addresses Central Ohio's moderate humidity with sustained cold winter conditions. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 5F ambient during polar vortex events drops below 32F in German Village brick cottages, causing interior condensation and frost that damages century-old plaster walls. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface above 48F and reduce condensation. Triple-pane with krypton fill eliminates condensation entirely for exposed suburban lots in Dublin and Powell where unobstructed northwest wind drives convective heat loss. Interior humidity management through kitchen and bathroom exhaust ventilation is essential during deep-freeze events.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Columbus frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable in Central Ohio freeze-thaw), .046"+ gauge vinyl (dimensionally stable, dominant on post-1980 suburban construction across Westerville, Hilliard, and Grove City), aluminum-clad wood (German Village and Victorian Village Commission-approved), and restoration-grade wood on landmark German Village cottages and Short North Victorian row houses. Pure aluminum is rare in Columbus residential due to thermal bridging. Dark frame colors show weathering in Columbus freeze-thaw within 10-12 years. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years. Termite barrier at grade level matters on wood frames given Columbus's position in the eastern termite zone.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Columbus window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Champion Windows (headquartered in Cincinnati OH) offers specific Ohio-market warranty terms. Nationwide Insurance (headquartered in Columbus) interacts with manufacturer warranties on Central Ohio hail-damage claims; familiarity with Nationwide claims procedures is valuable. Ohio has no statewide contractor license, so installer warranty enforceability centers on Franklin County building permit registration and insurance certificates. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Columbus lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes German Village, Victorian Village, Italian Village, Olde Town East, and Clintonville housing dating from the 1840s-1950s. Most post-WWII Columbus suburban construction (Westerville, Dublin, Hilliard) is post-1978 and lead-free. Ohio Department of Health Lead Poisoning Prevention Program administers state-level lead hazard requirements. Franklin County Public Health publishes neighborhood-specific lead-risk data by census tract. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 Columbus homes.`,
  },
  "kansas-city-mo": {
    localRebatesPara: `Kansas City rebate stacking: Evergy's residential efficiency programs return $40-$85 per qualified ENERGY STAR window on the Missouri-side service territory. Missouri Gas Energy (Spire) conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated KCMO homes. Kansas-side Johnson County properties in Overland Park and Leawood follow Kansas Gas Service (OneGas) rebates and Evergy Kansas programs. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Missouri Department of Natural Resources HELP loan program offers below-market-rate financing. Stack Evergy plus Spire/OneGas plus federal plus HELP for combined savings, verifying which state's utility programs apply to your specific address.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Kansas City sits at the convergence of Tornado Alley and the Great Plains hail corridor where severe-weather exposure is among the highest of any major US metro. The 2003 Harrisonville tornado, the 2019 Linwood-near-Indian-Creek tornado, and the May 2024 Overland Park supercell demonstrate recurring risk. Class 4 impact-rated glazing delivers 5-9% insurance premium reduction on most Kansas City policies with Shelter Insurance, American Family, and State Farm carriers dominant in the bi-state market. Laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing glazing provide combined hail and tornado-debris resistance. ASCE 7-22 rates Kansas City at 115 mph design wind speed.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Kansas City has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Kansas City Landmarks Commission governing locally designated districts including Janssen Place (Kansas City's first local historic district), Santa Fe Place, Scarritt Renaissance, Pendleton Heights, Union Hill, Quality Hill, Westport, Hyde Park (KCMO), Longfellow, and the 18th and Vine Historic District. Landmarks Commission review requires wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement matching original 1880s-1930s sash profiles, divided-lite configurations, and muntin widths on contributing facades. Country Club Plaza's 1920s Spanish Revival architecture requires specific Mediterranean-profile window details. Overland Park and Leawood on the Kansas side have separate municipal design review.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Kansas City condensation management addresses the continental prairie climate's wide temperature swings where winter relative humidity averages 68-74% when arctic air masses collide with Gulf moisture plumes along the Missouri River corridor. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 5F ambient during polar vortex events drops below 30F in Brookside and Waldo brick bungalows, causing heavy interior condensation and frost. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface above 48F. Summer humidity-driven condensation on cool air-conditioned window glass is a secondary Kansas City concern during July-August when dew points regularly reach 72-76F.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Kansas City frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable across the extreme continental temperature range from -10F to 110F), .046"+ gauge vinyl (dimensionally stable in prairie winter), aluminum-clad wood (Landmarks Commission-approved on historic districts), and restoration-grade wood on Janssen Place and Santa Fe Place landmarked Victorians. Pure aluminum conducts heat aggressively in both Kansas City winter cold and summer heat. Dark frame colors show weathering in KC freeze-thaw within 8-12 years. Hail-resistant frame and meeting-rail profiles are increasingly specified in Overland Park and Leawood suburban installations. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Kansas City window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Shelter Insurance (headquartered in Columbia MO) interacts with manufacturer warranties on Kansas City hail-damage claims; Class 4 impact-rated products provide smoother claims processing. Missouri Division of Professional Registration contractor status must be active at warranty claim time for Missouri-side enforceable claims; Kansas Attorney General registration governs Kansas-side warranty enforcement. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Kansas City lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Westport, Hyde Park, Scarritt Renaissance, Pendleton Heights, and Quality Hill historic district housing dating from the 1880s-1940s. Most post-WWII Kansas City suburban construction (Lee's Summit, Blue Springs, Overland Park) is post-1978 and lead-free. Missouri Department of Health and Senior Services Lead Poisoning Prevention Program administers Missouri-side requirements; Kansas Department of Health and Environment handles Johnson County properties. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$700.`,
  },
  "indianapolis-in": {
    localRebatesPara: `Indianapolis rebate stacking: AES Indiana's Home Energy Assessment program returns $40-$80 per qualified Northern-zone window on residential retrofits across the Marion County service territory. CenterPoint Energy Indiana gas conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes. Indiana's LIHEAP-funded weatherization program covers income-qualified full replacements through community action agencies. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Indiana state income tax deduction applies to qualifying home-improvement work. Stack AES Indiana plus CenterPoint plus federal plus state deduction for meaningful combined savings on Indy-metro retrofits.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Indianapolis is not a hurricane zone, but Central Indiana's position in the Hoosier Tornado Corridor produces 2-4 annual damaging severe-weather events. The March 2023 Greenfield tornado, the June 2023 Johnson County hail swath, and recurring spring supercell activity demonstrate consistent risk. Laminated outer panes on west-facing and south-facing glazing deliver 4-7% insurance premium reduction on most Indianapolis policies with Indiana Farm Bureau Insurance (headquartered in Indianapolis), Erie Insurance, and State Farm carriers. ASCE 7-22 rates Indianapolis at 105 mph design wind speed with flat-terrain Exposure C for most Hamilton and Marion County residential parcels.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Indianapolis has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Indianapolis Historic Preservation Commission (IHPC) governing locally designated districts including Lockerbie Square (Indiana's oldest historic district), Chatham-Arch, Fletcher Place, Herron-Morton Place, Old Northside, St. Joseph, Ransom Place, Cottage Home, Woodruff Place, and the Indiana Avenue Cultural District. IHPC review requires wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement matching original 1860s-1920s sash profiles, divided-lite configurations, and muntin widths on contributing facades. Lockerbie Square's ornate Italianate and Queen Anne window profiles with arched heads require specialty manufacturer orders. Review typically runs 4-8 weeks.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Indianapolis condensation management addresses Central Indiana's moderate humidity with sustained cold winter conditions and fully exposed flatland geography. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 0F ambient during polar vortex events drops below 30F in Meridian-Kessler and Broad Ripple brick bungalows, causing heavy interior condensation and frost that damages century-old plaster. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface above 48F. Triple-pane with krypton fill eliminates condensation for exposed suburban lots in Carmel and Fishers where unobstructed prairie-like northwest wind drives convective heat loss beyond what tree-canopy-sheltered intown neighborhoods experience.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Indianapolis frame material selection favors fiberglass (thermally stable in Central Indiana freeze-thaw), .046"+ gauge vinyl (dimensionally stable, dominant on post-1980 suburban construction across Carmel, Fishers, and Greenwood), aluminum-clad wood (IHPC-approved on Lockerbie Square, Chatham-Arch, and Fletcher Place landmark districts), and restoration-grade wood on landmark Queen Anne and Italianate homes. Pure aluminum is rare in Indy residential due to thermal bridging. Dark frame colors show weathering in Indianapolis freeze-thaw within 10-12 years. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years. Central Indiana wind exposure on unshielded lots requires reinforced meeting-rail and multi-chamber frame profiles.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Indianapolis window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass (Pella Corporation is headquartered in Pella IA with strong Indianapolis distribution). Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Champion Windows (headquartered in Cincinnati with strong Indiana presence) offers specific Midwest-market warranty terms. Indiana Farm Bureau Insurance (headquartered in Indianapolis) interacts with manufacturer warranties on Central Indiana hail-damage claims. Indiana has no statewide contractor license, so installer warranty enforceability centers on city building permit registration and insurance certificates. Installer workmanship warranties typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Indianapolis lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Lockerbie Square, Chatham-Arch, Fletcher Place, Herron-Morton Place, Old Northside, Broad Ripple, and Meridian-Kessler housing dating from the 1860s-1940s. Most post-WWII Indianapolis suburban construction (Carmel, Fishers, Greenwood) is post-1978 and lead-free. Indiana State Department of Health Lead and Healthy Homes Program administers state-level lead hazard requirements. Marion County Public Health Department publishes neighborhood-specific lead-risk data by census tract. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650.`,
  },
  "nashville-tn": {
    localRebatesPara: `Nashville rebate stacking: Nashville Electric Service's Home Energy Right program returns $35-$70 per qualified ENERGY STAR window on residential retrofits across the Davidson County service territory. Piedmont Natural Gas conservation rebates add parallel credits on gas-heated homes. Tennessee Valley Authority EnergyRight Solutions provides additional funding through NES on qualifying whole-home envelope upgrades. Federal 25C tax credit (30% of cost up to $600 annually under 2026 IRA rules) applies. Tennessee has no state income tax on wages, eliminating one variable from the cost equation. Stack NES plus Piedmont plus TVA EnergyRight plus federal for meaningful combined savings on Music City retrofits.`,
    impactRatedRulesPara: `Nashville sits squarely in Dixie Alley, the southeastern US severe-weather corridor that produces more nocturnal tornadoes per capita than traditional Tornado Alley. The devastating March 3, 2020 East Nashville EF3 tornado killed 25 people and destroyed thousands of structures along a path through Germantown, East Nashville, Donelson, and Hermitage. The December 2023 Clarksville outbreak reinforced the recurring risk pattern. Impact-rated glazing is not required by Metro Nashville building code but delivers 4-8% insurance premium reduction on most Davidson County policies. ASCE 7-22 rates Nashville at 115 mph design wind speed with mixed Exposure B/C for most residential parcels.`,
    historicSashRestrictionsPara: `Nashville has extensive historic preservation coverage under the Metro Nashville Historic Zoning Commission governing designated overlay districts including Edgefield, Lockeland Springs, East End, Sylvan Park, Richland-West End, Inglewood, Belmont-Hillsboro, Salemtown, Buena Vista, Greenwood, and the Marathon Village area. Metro Historic Zoning Commission review requires wood or aluminum-clad wood replacement matching original 1870s-1940s sash profiles, divided-lite configurations, and muntin widths on contributing facades. 12South and East Nashville shotgun-house windows from the 1890s-1910s require specific narrow-profile sash matching. Germantown's pre-Civil War brick homes have among Nashville's most prescriptive restoration requirements. Review typically runs 4-8 weeks.`,
    condensationManagementPara: `Nashville condensation management addresses the Cumberland Basin's humid-subtropical conditions where winter relative humidity averages 70-76% due to proximity to the Cumberland River and Percy Priest Lake moisture corridors. Interior surface temperature on single-pane at 15F ambient drops below 38F in East Nashville and Germantown brick shotgun houses, causing interior condensation that damages century-old plaster and wood trim. Dual-pane argon-filled IGUs with warm-edge spacer systems raise interior surface above 52F and reduce condensation. Summer humidity-driven condensation on cool air-conditioned glass is a secondary Nashville concern; HVAC dehumidification through properly sized equipment is essential during July-August humidity peaks.`,
    frameMaterialByRegionPara: `Nashville frame material selection favors vinyl (white or almond, UV-stabilized for Tennessee sun), fiberglass (thermally stable and humidity-resistant across the Cumberland Basin's 10F-to-100F annual range), aluminum-clad wood (Metro Historic Zoning Commission-approved on overlay districts), and restoration-grade wood on Edgefield and Germantown landmarked structures. Pure aluminum is common on 1960s-1980s Nashville ranch and split-level construction but conducts heat in both seasons. Dark frame colors fade in Nashville UV within 10-15 years on south and west exposures. Termite barrier at grade level is critical on wood frames given Nashville's position in the eastern subterranean termite zone. Fluoropolymer finishes hold color 12-15 years.`,
    warrantyTransferabilityPara: `Nashville window warranty transferability: Andersen 400 Series offers 20-year glass non-prorated. Pella Lifestyle offers 20-year glass. Marvin Ultimate transferable warranty runs 20 years. Milgard offers Full Lifetime Warranty. Nashville's humidity cycling and Dixie Alley severe-weather exposure stress both IGU seals and frame integrity. Tennessee Board for Licensing Contractors license (HI or BC classification) must be active at warranty claim time for enforceable claims. Verify license classification matches job dollar value because HI-license holders cannot perform work exceeding $25,000. Installer workmanship warranties from Nashville contractors typically run 5-15 years.`,
    leadSafeCertPara: `Nashville lead-safe certification: EPA RRP applies to pre-1978 homes, which includes Germantown, Edgefield, Lockeland Springs, East End, Sylvan Park, and Richland-West End housing dating from the 1850s-1940s. Most post-WWII Nashville suburban construction (Brentwood, Franklin, Hendersonville) is post-1978 and lead-free. Tennessee Department of Environment and Conservation Lead-Based Paint Program administers state-level requirements. Metro Nashville Public Health Department publishes lead-hazard information for older Davidson County neighborhoods. Certified firms only may perform window replacement scope where lead paint may be disturbed. Lead-paint testing before scope begins typically runs $250-$650 on pre-1978 Nashville homes.`,
  },
};

